00:02:06.926 --> 00:02:08.765
Everything stays really solid.

00:02:09.229 --> 00:02:10.349
This is the kitchen.

00:02:10.416 --> 00:02:12.599
-That's nice,
the cooking smoke is out here.

00:02:12.666 --> 00:02:16.666
Yeah. Everything. All the cooking is.
I don't want that smell inside.

00:02:18.884 --> 00:02:20.544
[Diesel engine starts]

00:02:23.034 --> 00:02:27.263
So Bob, you're on the road how much
out of the year? Living out of this?

00:02:27.330 --> 00:02:30.250
-All the time.
This is where I live. This is my home.

00:02:30.317 --> 00:02:31.435
Welcome to my home.

00:02:31.915 --> 00:02:34.363
-Okay. So what sparked this lifestyle?

00:02:34.430 --> 00:02:36.158
I was in radio. So I got fired.

00:02:36.225 --> 00:02:38.563
I don't know
how many times I've been fired.

00:02:38.630 --> 00:02:41.102
I love radio.
But radio does not love me back.

00:02:41.169 --> 00:02:44.193
So I decided I thought
I'll find a better business.

00:02:44.260 --> 00:02:45.805
I'll start podcasting.

00:02:46.433 --> 00:02:49.813
So I was living in a duplex
and I had my podcast.

00:02:49.880 --> 00:02:53.423
My idea was that I was gonna
sell advertising like local radio.

00:02:53.490 --> 00:02:56.545
Well it worked okay.
I actually had a couple of good years.

00:02:56.619 --> 00:02:59.176
And then everybody and his brother
got a podcast.

00:02:59.243 --> 00:03:01.481
So around COVID time

00:03:01.548 --> 00:03:05.239
I found myself thinking this is ridiculous.

00:03:05.306 --> 00:03:08.947
And there was almost a voice that said,

00:03:09.533 --> 00:03:10.416
Go!

00:03:10.875 --> 00:03:11.952
Just go!

00:03:12.426 --> 00:03:13.887
It kept getting louder.

00:03:13.954 --> 00:03:16.712
So I basically threw everything away,

00:03:16.779 --> 00:03:19.366
or sold everything, or gave it away.

00:03:19.433 --> 00:03:22.404
And moved into a 2000 Ford ambulance.

00:03:22.471 --> 00:03:25.899
So you were one of those first guys
doing the ambulance living right?

00:03:25.966 --> 00:03:30.268
-I think I might have been the first.
-Big claim. That's a popular thing now.

00:03:30.335 --> 00:03:33.543
Which drove me crazy.
It was like, "Is that an ambulance?"

00:03:34.402 --> 00:03:37.943
'Cause everybody wanted…
Well good luck redoing a new fire truck.

00:03:38.485 --> 00:03:40.628
-Okay so Bob, Sedona here.

00:03:40.695 --> 00:03:44.154
This is one of the so called vortexes.

00:03:44.221 --> 00:03:47.098
-Have you heard of these?
-I have heard of the vortexes.

00:03:47.165 --> 00:03:48.703
And I'm already feeling it.

00:03:48.770 --> 00:03:51.176
-Are you feeling the vortex energy?

00:03:51.243 --> 00:03:54.250
So there's something energetically
that happens. So they say.

00:03:54.317 --> 00:03:56.998
Apparently.
Have you heard about the orbs in Sedona?

00:03:57.065 --> 00:03:58.150
-No.

00:03:58.217 --> 00:04:02.183
Apparently there's orbs in Sedona.
They say so on YouTube so it must be true.

00:04:02.250 --> 00:04:04.426
And this is all iron
in these mountains too.

00:04:04.493 --> 00:04:05.888
-That's what makes it red?

00:04:05.955 --> 00:04:08.029
But it's also a conductor.

00:04:08.096 --> 00:04:09.746
-Are you a believer, Bob?

00:04:09.813 --> 00:04:10.989
I mean the vortexes?

00:04:12.016 --> 00:04:13.786
Or something powerful here?

00:04:13.853 --> 00:04:16.824
There's something powerful.
All of Arizona is mystical.

00:04:16.891 --> 00:04:18.814
The entire Southwest is mystical.

00:04:18.881 --> 00:04:21.992
Because a lot of it,
millions of years ago was underwater.

00:04:22.059 --> 00:04:23.181
It was an ocean.

00:04:23.248 --> 00:04:27.400
So just imagine if the Atlantic Ocean
dried up someday and it was like this.

00:04:27.467 --> 00:04:30.923
[Peter] Okay so Sedona,
as we can see, there's money here.

00:04:30.990 --> 00:04:33.945
A lot of people want to come
for this beautiful environment.

00:04:34.012 --> 00:04:37.364
Sort of a bubbled up place,
removed from society. That's how I feel.

00:04:37.431 --> 00:04:41.476
-Well I think a lot of people
are trying to escape the corporate world.

00:04:41.543 --> 00:04:43.683
And it depends on what your resources are.

00:04:43.750 --> 00:04:46.554
If you have a lot of resource
you can do a lot of things.

00:04:46.621 --> 00:04:50.423
If you don't have a lot of resource
you go out in a 20 year old ambulance.

00:04:50.490 --> 00:04:52.847
-So Bob, a lot of my videos as you know,

00:04:52.914 --> 00:04:55.992
'cause you were in one
that was three years ago in Quartzsite.

00:04:56.059 --> 00:04:58.289
-Wow.
-Can you believe that? Three years ago.

00:04:58.356 --> 00:05:00.794
Bob and I met, southern Arizona.

00:05:00.861 --> 00:05:02.528
Southwestern Arizona.

00:05:02.595 --> 00:05:05.244
Bob was in his early stage
of living off the grid.

00:05:05.311 --> 00:05:06.485
We've kept in touch.

00:05:06.552 --> 00:05:09.542
We sort of like
exchanged notes on the country.

00:05:09.609 --> 00:05:13.640
'Cause you're going granular in America.
You go down the back roads.

00:05:13.707 --> 00:05:15.536
I hate highways. I hate the freeway.

00:05:15.603 --> 00:05:18.459
I stay off the freeway
unless I absolutely have to use it.

00:05:18.526 --> 00:05:21.301
-So the point of this video
is to get into that

00:05:21.368 --> 00:05:23.705
really interesting component of America

00:05:23.772 --> 00:05:27.537
where when you go granular
all of these different worlds open up.

00:05:28.269 --> 00:05:30.569
More so than most countries I've been to.

00:05:30.636 --> 00:05:31.519
Oh yeah.

00:05:31.586 --> 00:05:35.288
Because every state has a different
legal history

00:05:35.355 --> 00:05:36.711
and a social history.

00:05:36.778 --> 00:05:40.094
Even though people think
it's all one country, especially the West.

00:05:40.161 --> 00:05:43.684
Each state had its own legal framework
when it became a territory.

00:05:43.751 --> 00:05:48.481
Yes, according to the rules
of how you admit states to the union.

00:05:48.548 --> 00:05:51.174
But most of these states just came about.

00:05:51.651 --> 00:05:52.677
This is amazing.

00:05:52.744 --> 00:05:56.353
[Peter] Yeah this is really cool.
Sort of the tourist center I would say.

00:05:56.420 --> 00:05:59.101
Or the part that's done really well,
Tlacapaque.

00:05:59.650 --> 00:06:02.407
Done in, what is that, a Spanish style?

00:06:02.474 --> 00:06:03.929
Sort of a Pueblo style?

00:06:03.996 --> 00:06:07.219
[Bob] Pueblo, Hacienda, Spanish, Mexican.

00:06:07.286 --> 00:06:11.017
-You can see the money in this town.
Just look at these roundabouts, Bob.

00:06:11.084 --> 00:06:13.980
-The art there.
-We've spent a lot of money on the art.

00:06:14.047 --> 00:06:17.258
And this place brings in,
I was reading last night,

00:06:17.325 --> 00:06:19.388
roughly 3 million tourists a year.

00:06:19.779 --> 00:06:21.392
-Really?
-From around the world.

00:06:21.459 --> 00:06:25.143
A lot of people come for
spirituality, wellness.

00:06:25.210 --> 00:06:26.653
See a lot of this going on.

00:06:26.720 --> 00:06:28.902
The center for the new age.
It's right here.

00:06:28.969 --> 00:06:30.658
[Peter] You have UFO tours.

00:06:31.922 --> 00:06:33.674
[Peter] You got a lot of hiking.

00:06:34.065 --> 00:06:35.995
[Peter] These trails go back forever.

00:06:36.062 --> 00:06:40.210
If I'm to guess
I think these are probably $3 million.

00:06:40.277 --> 00:06:41.943
-Something like that.
-A bargain.

00:06:42.351 --> 00:06:43.704
A bargain at any price.

00:06:44.271 --> 00:06:47.006
-You got a lot of
new construction happening.

00:06:47.073 --> 00:06:49.606
And with those views, tough to beat.

00:06:49.680 --> 00:06:53.805
I mean from all the country you've seen,
one of the most beautiful places, right?

00:06:53.872 --> 00:06:55.048
-Sedona? Absolutely.

00:06:55.759 --> 00:07:00.170
So there's different resources and people
have different ways of breaking free.

00:07:00.237 --> 00:07:02.846
If you're happy
in your corporate life, good for you.

00:07:02.913 --> 00:07:05.825
If you have a job
that calls on your passion, good for you.

00:07:05.892 --> 00:07:09.128
But for many people in the corporate world
it seems to be hollow.

00:07:09.195 --> 00:07:11.030
To me, travel,

00:07:11.097 --> 00:07:14.038
and having the tool to travel in,
which is Unit 11…

00:07:14.467 --> 00:07:17.270
-That's the name of this rig?
-This rig is called Unit 11.

00:07:17.337 --> 00:07:18.844
You love this, Bob, don't you?

00:07:18.911 --> 00:07:21.503
Well it works. I mean I use all that stuff.

00:07:21.570 --> 00:07:25.394
-Left flood, the rear flood, all that stuff
-How about Siren Horn?

00:07:25.461 --> 00:07:26.912
[flips switches]

00:07:28.186 --> 00:07:29.069
[horn honks]

00:07:30.102 --> 00:07:32.220
That's why we don't use it too much.

00:07:32.537 --> 00:07:33.431
[Peter chuckles]

00:07:33.498 --> 00:07:36.689
So did you basically
regress back to 16, Bob?

00:07:36.756 --> 00:07:38.725
I am 12 to 15 years old.

00:07:38.792 --> 00:07:42.099
And there's drawbacks to this life
but, you know, on balance,

00:07:42.166 --> 00:07:44.695
when you hit the highs they are so high.

00:07:44.762 --> 00:07:47.186
-When you have an experience like this…
-Right.

00:07:47.253 --> 00:07:49.628
It's amazing
and that makes it all worth it.

00:07:49.695 --> 00:07:51.111
I don't know what day it is.

00:07:51.178 --> 00:07:54.413
I don't have to worry about
where I'm gonna go tomorrow.

00:07:55.308 --> 00:07:56.437
[Western music]

00:08:16.529 --> 00:08:18.682
[Bob] It's a pretty majestic way to travel.

00:08:18.749 --> 00:08:19.923
Yeah it is cool.

00:08:19.990 --> 00:08:21.322
It's so smooth too.

00:08:21.945 --> 00:08:23.716
Like these seats just bounce.

00:08:23.783 --> 00:08:25.271
-Yeah we have air ride.

00:08:25.338 --> 00:08:27.834
So this is all called Verde Valley.

00:08:27.901 --> 00:08:31.342
And we're like 15 minutes
from Sedona. That's it.

00:08:31.409 --> 00:08:33.379
Amazing. Completely different world.

00:08:33.446 --> 00:08:35.348
Now we're moving into the mining area.

00:08:35.415 --> 00:08:37.683
So we're about to cross
an invisible line Bob.

00:08:37.750 --> 00:08:41.892
Basically yes we are going to cross
an invisible line from the red rocks

00:08:41.959 --> 00:08:45.188
into the mining history of Arizona.

00:08:45.769 --> 00:08:48.635
-And you know what's great
about this part of the state is

00:08:48.702 --> 00:08:52.247
there's just so much land.
All this is state or federal land I think.

00:08:52.314 --> 00:08:55.796
So there's just a massive buffer zone
between the towns.

00:08:55.863 --> 00:08:57.904
Sedona to here there is no development.

00:08:57.971 --> 00:09:01.827
Arizona should be seen
as much as possible the way it was.

00:09:02.431 --> 00:09:04.711
Can you imagine
coming out here in the 1920s?

00:09:04.778 --> 00:09:07.301
None of this was here. The roads were dirt.

00:09:07.368 --> 00:09:10.700
You'd be driving a Model T
or a 12-cylinder Buick.

00:09:10.767 --> 00:09:13.769
-No air conditioning.
-We don't have air conditioning either.

00:09:13.836 --> 00:09:16.530
-That's true.
-This is a summer simulator.

00:09:16.989 --> 00:09:20.333
You've gonna have windows open
because the heat is always on?

00:09:20.400 --> 00:09:22.528
You can't get the heat off.
It's a Minnesota truck.

00:09:22.595 --> 00:09:24.864
June, and you're using the heat.

00:09:24.946 --> 00:09:29.299
I can't figure out how to get the heat off.
I'm gonna have to work on that.

00:09:30.776 --> 00:09:33.283
[Peter] You have a lot of respect
for this vehicle.

00:09:33.350 --> 00:09:37.307
-Yeah that's a great RV.
That's got the same engine I have probably.

00:09:37.374 --> 00:09:38.433
That is… or a cat.

00:09:39.270 --> 00:09:42.131
It's a Bluebird bus
that was turned into an RV.

00:09:42.198 --> 00:09:45.451
It's called a Wanderlust
or Wanderer or something like that.

00:09:45.518 --> 00:09:46.903
Pretty cool. Look at that.

00:09:46.970 --> 00:09:49.287
-Old '50s gas station.
-Wow that's cool.

00:09:49.354 --> 00:09:50.857
Now it's a restaurant.

00:09:50.924 --> 00:09:54.677
And we're not stopping here Bob
but this is Cottonwood.

00:09:54.744 --> 00:09:57.414
-Your classic Western town right?
-Classic.

00:09:58.730 --> 00:10:01.055
[Bob] Historic Clarkdale. Here we are.

00:10:01.122 --> 00:10:03.459
[Peter] And it was a total company town.

00:10:03.526 --> 00:10:07.000
-Yeah a company town.
-William Clark I believe is the man's name.

00:10:07.067 --> 00:10:10.265
-Yeah that's the guy.
-It was basically a smelter town.

00:10:10.332 --> 00:10:13.400
all the iron ore
was coming down here from the mountain.

00:10:13.467 --> 00:10:15.157
Also mining services.

00:10:15.224 --> 00:10:17.142
So they served the mine from down here

00:10:17.209 --> 00:10:20.029
and commercial services of other types.

00:10:20.097 --> 00:10:23.323
Banks.
You know, Jerome was the mining center.

00:10:23.831 --> 00:10:26.867
-Look at this. Beautiful architecture.
-Wow.

00:10:26.934 --> 00:10:29.534
-Copper museum.
-And that's the old high school.

00:10:30.042 --> 00:10:33.455
So Bob when you pull into a town
you need to take up three spaces?

00:10:33.522 --> 00:10:36.502
Yeah I never parallel park.
You don't even think about that.

00:10:36.569 --> 00:10:38.216
[truck reverse alarm beeping]

00:10:46.579 --> 00:10:50.021
[Peter] The state of Arizona
is a long life and a little bit.

00:10:50.088 --> 00:10:50.971
That's it.

00:10:51.600 --> 00:10:53.386
So total company town.

00:10:53.453 --> 00:10:55.263
Company owned all the real estate,

00:10:55.330 --> 00:10:57.458
the school, the hospitals.

00:10:57.525 --> 00:10:59.190
So if you work for the mine

00:10:59.257 --> 00:11:01.472
they assign you a house
or did you pay rent?

00:11:01.539 --> 00:11:04.894
-I know in a lot of places in the country
you're paid in scrip.

00:11:04.961 --> 00:11:09.803
Which is company currency that worked
in the company town but nowhere else.

00:11:09.870 --> 00:11:11.844
-Okay.
-So get paid from the mine.

00:11:12.500 --> 00:11:15.022
-You're like I need to get out of here.
-You can't.

00:11:15.089 --> 00:11:17.713
-Your money's not going anywhere.
-Yeah, well…

00:11:17.780 --> 00:11:20.261
-My family's from a mining town.
-Oh this is cool.

00:11:20.328 --> 00:11:24.958
There were gun battles between
the union and the mining interests.

00:11:25.462 --> 00:11:28.090
This is great though.
You can see the bones are here.

00:11:28.157 --> 00:11:30.869
Had its moment in the past obviously.

00:11:30.936 --> 00:11:33.285
Looks like some comeback happening.

00:11:33.352 --> 00:11:35.893
So the founder, Clark, was a politician.

00:11:36.851 --> 00:11:40.144
Clark County,
where Las Vegas is, named after him.

00:11:40.211 --> 00:11:41.567
-Oh really?
-Same Clark

00:11:41.634 --> 00:11:44.377
Look at this.
Got the block glass up here.

00:11:44.444 --> 00:11:48.534
-The mining started in Arizona
in probably the late 1870s

00:11:48.601 --> 00:11:49.876
maybe a little sooner.

00:11:50.237 --> 00:11:52.379
And kind of peaked in the. 1920s.

00:11:52.446 --> 00:11:54.064
-[man] How you doing?
-What's up?

00:11:54.131 --> 00:11:56.531
-I've seen your videos.
-Oh thank you.

00:11:56.598 --> 00:11:58.238
Guys what's going on here?

00:11:58.305 --> 00:12:00.153
Uh this is the owner.

00:12:00.220 --> 00:12:01.823
-You're the owner?
-One of them.

00:12:01.890 --> 00:12:04.557
-Can I show what's going on?
-Just building a bar.

00:12:04.624 --> 00:12:06.971
Building a bar? Nice. Oh my God.

00:12:07.890 --> 00:12:09.306
-Gorgeous. What's your name?

00:12:09.373 --> 00:12:11.430
-I'm Steve. Nice to meet you.
-Peter.

00:12:11.497 --> 00:12:13.818
It's the old newsstand.
There used to be a bar.

00:12:13.885 --> 00:12:16.536
-You're from Clarkdale?
-Yeah. Born and raised.

00:12:16.603 --> 00:12:19.736
Went down when the mine went down?
Now it's coming back?

00:12:19.803 --> 00:12:22.221
Now it's coming back.
Cement plant came to town.

00:12:22.288 --> 00:12:23.376
-Cement plant?
-Yeah.

00:12:23.443 --> 00:12:25.653
Wine Country. Sedona helps.

00:12:25.720 --> 00:12:28.247
-Wine Country?
-Yeah. Maynard. The guy from Tool.

00:12:28.314 --> 00:12:31.177
He opened his winery and kinda
opened the floodgates.

00:12:31.244 --> 00:12:32.919
-He lives up in Jerome right?
-Yeah.

00:12:32.986 --> 00:12:35.523
-We put a rooftop bar up.
-Oh let's check it out.

00:12:35.590 --> 00:12:38.374
Is this original? This stuff?

00:12:38.441 --> 00:12:40.726
-No we put that all in.
-It's beautiful.

00:12:41.206 --> 00:12:43.498
One of the oldest
liquor licenses in Arizona.

00:12:43.565 --> 00:12:46.199
-When are you opening?
-A month or two.

00:12:46.266 --> 00:12:50.152
-What kind of food are you gonna have?
-Flatbreads, salads, sandwiches.

00:12:50.219 --> 00:12:51.728
That sounds good.

00:12:51.795 --> 00:12:54.781
-Okay there's the cement factory.
-Yeah, the cement plant.

00:12:54.848 --> 00:12:57.420
-So some people work there.
-Yep and there's Sedona.

00:12:57.487 --> 00:12:58.845
-Up on those rocks?
-Yep.

00:12:58.912 --> 00:13:00.399
Look at these plots.

00:13:00.466 --> 00:13:02.648
-Down for the bathrooms.
-This is so cool.

00:13:02.715 --> 00:13:05.215
This is where you meet
the love of your life right?

00:13:05.282 --> 00:13:07.204
There's a fire pit we're putting in.

00:13:07.271 --> 00:13:09.683
-We met at the old newsstand.
-[chuckling]

00:13:10.987 --> 00:13:13.452
-And this is…
-Look at this.

00:13:13.519 --> 00:13:15.578
The bar you serve drinks out of.

00:13:15.645 --> 00:13:17.057
[Peter] This is so cool.

00:13:17.610 --> 00:13:18.731
-Almost there.

00:13:19.154 --> 00:13:21.753
So all the buildings,
we're gonna walk through them

00:13:21.820 --> 00:13:24.704
but all done in
a cool old school style there.

00:13:24.771 --> 00:13:26.606
Yeah 1914's when this was built.

00:13:26.673 --> 00:13:29.773
Okay so the main drag here,
that's vacant right?

00:13:29.840 --> 00:13:31.538
-This was vacant.
-Yep.

00:13:31.618 --> 00:13:33.940
They're redoing the gas station.

00:13:34.627 --> 00:13:37.778
-It's the kayak company.
-Old '50's gas station.

00:13:37.845 --> 00:13:40.619
The kayak company bought it.
They do tours of the river.

00:13:40.686 --> 00:13:41.569
Beautiful.

00:13:41.636 --> 00:13:45.092
They're gonna do a food court
and it looks like it's gonna be awesome.

00:13:45.159 --> 00:13:47.626
-That's gonna be nice.
-Are you fired up on this?

00:13:47.693 --> 00:13:48.595
Yeah.

00:13:48.662 --> 00:13:50.762
It's gonna be like Friday night in Jerome.

00:13:50.829 --> 00:13:52.024
-Right?

00:13:52.091 --> 00:13:55.353
So we're gonna Jerome next
but different vibe than here right?

00:13:55.420 --> 00:13:58.382
Oh yeah.
A small ghost town, kinda hippie vibe.

00:13:58.989 --> 00:14:00.509
Really cool. Parking's awful.

00:14:01.300 --> 00:14:05.016
-That's no problem for what we're driving.
-We're driving an old fire engine.

00:14:05.083 --> 00:14:06.912
We're not gonna be parking in Jerome.

00:14:07.670 --> 00:14:10.347
-Take care you guys. Awesome work.
-You too brother.

00:14:10.414 --> 00:14:11.584
You did an awesome job.

00:14:11.651 --> 00:14:13.146
We're just painting, man.

00:14:13.213 --> 00:14:15.298
-You guys live in town?
-Cottonwood.

00:14:15.365 --> 00:14:18.378
-Cottonwood alright.
-I watch your videos with my girlfriend.

00:14:18.445 --> 00:14:20.993
We watched the one
with the most remote tribe.

00:14:21.060 --> 00:14:22.733
You got a rez right up here.

00:14:22.800 --> 00:14:24.406
-Yavapai Apache.
-Yeah.

00:14:25.150 --> 00:14:27.233
-We're gonna go there.
-Right now?

00:14:27.300 --> 00:14:29.680
-Yeah in a little bit.
-Nice seeing you brother.

00:14:29.747 --> 00:14:30.994
See you guys. Thank you.

00:14:32.102 --> 00:14:34.043
Some more things banging in here.

00:14:36.209 --> 00:14:39.721
Isn't it great seeing that in these towns?
There's a revival happening.

00:14:39.788 --> 00:14:43.069
An old theater here.
Check this out with the box office.

00:14:43.143 --> 00:14:46.866
Well small towns are gonna come back
because they're better places to live.

00:14:46.933 --> 00:14:47.990
Plain and simple.

00:14:48.057 --> 00:14:50.889
If you want to get away
from the grind this is the place.

00:14:50.956 --> 00:14:53.637
Obviously you have to figure out
what you're gonna do.

00:14:53.704 --> 00:14:57.412
-Yeah exactly.
Look at that '50s gas station coming back.

00:14:58.060 --> 00:14:59.238
Brewery in town.

00:14:59.810 --> 00:15:02.269
But you gotta love it.
Even back in the day,

00:15:02.725 --> 00:15:04.450
the company vision right?

00:15:04.517 --> 00:15:08.407
Make it nice enough
where people want to stay. That's my guess.

00:15:08.474 --> 00:15:11.133
Because they didn't seem to
cut corners here right?

00:15:11.200 --> 00:15:12.778
Big park in the middle.

00:15:12.845 --> 00:15:14.680
Bungalow architecture here.

00:15:14.747 --> 00:15:17.283
Craftsmen. A little craftsmen's.

00:15:17.355 --> 00:15:18.509
Tudor revival.

00:15:19.027 --> 00:15:22.515
Architects planned and designed
Clarkdale as a model town.

00:15:23.035 --> 00:15:26.535
And phases of construction that allowed
architectural styles to evolve.

00:15:27.226 --> 00:15:30.131
Back in the day
you could have four kids in there easily.

00:15:30.198 --> 00:15:31.506
-Yeah.
-Maybe four or five.

00:15:31.573 --> 00:15:33.999
[Bob] How much
do you figure that is? $400,000?

00:15:34.066 --> 00:15:36.300
-I checked Zillow. It's around that.

00:15:36.367 --> 00:15:38.957
-And they're gorgeous.
-This one's done really well.

00:15:39.024 --> 00:15:43.545
The idea was to plan the community
and copper is incredibly lucrative.

00:15:43.612 --> 00:15:45.748
-Especially in those days.
-And now too.

00:15:46.119 --> 00:15:48.490
If you were a miner
this is a pretty good life.

00:15:48.557 --> 00:15:50.722
Except you're probably
being paid in script.

00:15:50.789 --> 00:15:52.046
Except the work.

00:15:52.113 --> 00:15:54.564
-Tough work.
-Well you have to do the mining work.

00:15:54.631 --> 00:15:58.112
But people in those eras
were not adverse to hard work

00:15:58.179 --> 00:15:59.994
because there wasn't any other work.

00:16:00.061 --> 00:16:02.457
-Exactly.
-You could work in an office somewhere

00:16:02.524 --> 00:16:05.564
but I mean you're born
at the turn of the century.

00:16:05.631 --> 00:16:09.264
What would you know how to do?
You'd know how to ride a horse, hunt,

00:16:09.686 --> 00:16:11.097
work on the farm.

00:16:11.495 --> 00:16:13.669
So you could adapt farm workers

00:16:13.736 --> 00:16:16.649
and other workers like that
for mining very easily.

00:16:16.716 --> 00:16:18.277
A lot of them were immigrants.

00:16:18.344 --> 00:16:22.540
Up in the UP they came from Cornwall
or whatever it was called, Cornish.

00:16:22.607 --> 00:16:24.398
-Finland.
-Finland.

00:16:24.465 --> 00:16:27.117
In northern Minnesota
they came from Eastern Europe.

00:16:27.184 --> 00:16:28.455
Yeah. A lot of Italians.

00:16:28.522 --> 00:16:32.409
They call them the Bohunks up there.
Italians, Hungarians, Czechs.

00:16:32.865 --> 00:16:36.929
And then in the Ohio River Valley
and in West Virginia they came from Wales.

00:16:36.996 --> 00:16:38.692
And my people are all from Wales.

00:16:38.759 --> 00:16:42.003
They came to this country
to mine down in central Ohio.

00:16:42.070 --> 00:16:44.438
-This is so cool huh?
Just these little details.

00:16:44.505 --> 00:16:46.684
-This is beautiful. I wonder what this was.

00:16:46.751 --> 00:16:48.506
I guess some kind of train station.

00:16:48.573 --> 00:16:50.631
-So this is a former company town

00:16:50.698 --> 00:16:53.366
but in Arizona
there are two that are still operating.

00:16:53.433 --> 00:16:56.048
Bagdad, Arizona, Morenci, Arizona.

00:16:56.115 --> 00:16:58.471
Everyone in those towns
works for the company.

00:16:58.538 --> 00:17:02.123
-What does the company do?
-Freeport-McMoRan, copper.

00:17:02.190 --> 00:17:04.399
-Oh. Well God knows we need copper.
-We do.

00:17:04.906 --> 00:17:08.534
-If you like electricity.
-If you like electricity you need copper.

00:17:08.601 --> 00:17:09.484
Men's lounge.

00:17:09.551 --> 00:17:12.807
So back in the day
we had the ladies lounge over there.

00:17:12.880 --> 00:17:15.649
They just created
a lot of social things here I bet.

00:17:15.716 --> 00:17:18.639
You get people in the community,
wanting to be here.

00:17:18.706 --> 00:17:19.834
Is that what that is?

00:17:19.901 --> 00:17:20.784
-I'm sure if…

00:17:21.313 --> 00:17:23.372
[Bob] Oh, sorry.
-[woman] It's okay.

00:17:25.380 --> 00:17:27.073
No longer just a men's lounge.

00:17:27.140 --> 00:17:29.913
Apparently they're doing
some serious stuff in there.

00:17:29.980 --> 00:17:33.853
Excuse me. Do you know the story
behind the men's lounge female's lounge?

00:17:33.920 --> 00:17:35.839
-Can we walk in that building?
-Yeah.

00:17:35.906 --> 00:17:39.049
The men would go off
and have their pool time.

00:17:39.116 --> 00:17:41.187
-You know pool tables, billiards.
-Okay.

00:17:41.254 --> 00:17:44.063
And the ladies
would come in here and have tea time.

00:17:44.130 --> 00:17:47.063
Cooking and the ladies lounge.

00:17:47.130 --> 00:17:48.088
Vice mayor?

00:17:48.155 --> 00:17:49.270
[Bob] Oh my God!

00:17:49.337 --> 00:17:51.108
Okay we found the right person.

00:17:51.175 --> 00:17:53.258
Oh wow. Look at this.

00:17:53.325 --> 00:17:55.081
-Are you doing stuff in here?
-Yeah.

00:17:55.148 --> 00:17:58.763
As a matter of fact our local high school
has their senior prom in here.

00:17:58.830 --> 00:18:00.516
We just approved that.

00:18:00.583 --> 00:18:02.382
Uh oh. This guy.

00:18:02.783 --> 00:18:03.834
-Here's Johnny!

00:18:03.901 --> 00:18:05.143
[chuckling]

00:18:05.210 --> 00:18:07.919
-Do you need me to kick him out?
-No.

00:18:07.986 --> 00:18:09.686
-Nice performance, Bob.
-Thank you.

00:18:09.753 --> 00:18:13.177
Are you getting many young people
or is this more of a retiree place?

00:18:13.244 --> 00:18:15.764
No, there's this is
a great town to raise families.

00:18:15.831 --> 00:18:16.810
You want families?

00:18:16.877 --> 00:18:18.611
Absolutely. Absolutely.

00:18:18.685 --> 00:18:21.203
And it's a lot of
generational growth here.

00:18:21.270 --> 00:18:22.952
A lot of town pride here Debbie?

00:18:23.019 --> 00:18:24.631
Absolutely. A lot of town pride.

00:18:24.698 --> 00:18:26.577
It's a small town but we're mighty.

00:18:26.644 --> 00:18:28.029
We have a lot of events.

00:18:28.096 --> 00:18:31.015
We just opened a new park down the hill

00:18:31.082 --> 00:18:32.591
that's state of the art.

00:18:32.658 --> 00:18:36.946
[Peter] Oh look at this.
Oh my God. This is fantastic. Wow.

00:18:37.013 --> 00:18:39.549
So what's funding this town? Tax revenue?

00:18:39.616 --> 00:18:41.753
-You got something else coming in?
-Tax revenue.

00:18:41.820 --> 00:18:45.323
Actually more than our general fund
in grant money that has come in

00:18:45.390 --> 00:18:47.013
both federal, state.

00:18:47.080 --> 00:18:49.487
-They just want to hold
on to this history here

00:18:49.554 --> 00:18:52.276
and make sure this place thrives
because it's unique.

00:18:52.343 --> 00:18:53.977
-Is that what it is?
-Right.

00:18:54.047 --> 00:18:55.865
You're not gonna get this in Sedona.

00:18:55.932 --> 00:18:57.593
This old world feeling.

00:18:57.660 --> 00:18:58.748
No.

00:18:58.815 --> 00:19:01.511
This here, and Jerome, Cottonwood,

00:19:01.578 --> 00:19:03.947
all are very historic to the area.

00:19:06.667 --> 00:19:09.373
-Should we hit the road Bob?
-Yeah let's do it.

00:19:16.676 --> 00:19:19.015
[Peter] Here we are, Yavapai Apache Tribe.

00:19:19.384 --> 00:19:22.542
"Welcome. You are entering
the Yavapai Apache Nation."

00:19:22.609 --> 00:19:26.744
"You have voluntarily submitted yourself
to the laws and jurisdiction

00:19:26.811 --> 00:19:28.886
of the Yavapai Apache Nation."

00:19:30.526 --> 00:19:33.503
So we're in a different jurisdiction.
Just like that.

00:19:33.570 --> 00:19:35.730
Pass a border and we're in.

00:19:36.329 --> 00:19:37.343
They got gates too.

00:19:37.410 --> 00:19:40.313
-They can gate it off.
-Drugs are not welcome by the way.

00:19:40.380 --> 00:19:42.004
Local police can't come in here.

00:19:42.071 --> 00:19:45.521
I don't know how it works here
but a lot of times it's just sheriffs.

00:19:45.588 --> 00:19:47.764
They have to be accompanied
by local police.

00:19:47.831 --> 00:19:50.131
They have their own Tribal police.

00:19:50.615 --> 00:19:52.923
So here we go guys.
This is what it looks like.

00:19:53.416 --> 00:19:56.967
And so in Verde Valley
there are five reservations.

00:19:57.034 --> 00:19:57.917
Very small.

00:19:58.413 --> 00:20:00.980
And they have a casino.
One of them has a casino.

00:20:01.565 --> 00:20:05.127
[Bob] So Yavapai and Apache
are two different tribes.

00:20:05.194 --> 00:20:09.173
They're together on the reservation but
historically they were different tribes.

00:20:09.240 --> 00:20:11.880
They're like "What is that?!"

00:20:13.696 --> 00:20:15.606
So in Verde Valley here

00:20:15.673 --> 00:20:19.013
there are roughly 2,200 Natives.

00:20:19.382 --> 00:20:21.590
On this res around 200.

00:20:22.020 --> 00:20:24.289
And nobody's out.
I'd love to talk to someone.

00:20:24.356 --> 00:20:25.993
There's some boarded up homes.

00:20:26.624 --> 00:20:29.180
-These were probably built
by the US government.

00:20:29.247 --> 00:20:31.601
-So they left when? What was it? 1870?

00:20:32.008 --> 00:20:33.741
-Out of Clarkdale?
-They came back.

00:20:33.808 --> 00:20:38.039
-I don't remember what year.
-They came back before 1912 I believe.

00:20:38.106 --> 00:20:40.221
They didn't leave. They were escorted out.

00:20:40.288 --> 00:20:42.483
-They were escorted to San Carlos.
-Yeah.

00:20:42.892 --> 00:20:45.800
That reservation.
A couple hundred miles from here.

00:20:46.629 --> 00:20:49.953
I think that's about it Bob.
There's just a few suburban streets.

00:20:50.020 --> 00:20:51.653
Again juxtapositioning.

00:20:51.720 --> 00:20:53.264
So there you go guys.

00:20:53.331 --> 00:20:55.612
You want to put a label on Arizona,
good luck.

00:20:55.679 --> 00:20:59.240
You want to put a label on
a small part of Arizona right?

00:20:59.307 --> 00:21:02.014
Sedona and here, two different worlds.

00:21:02.081 --> 00:21:04.451
Here we got a Oova smoke shop.

00:21:04.518 --> 00:21:05.733
Drive-thru.

00:21:05.800 --> 00:21:08.027
And then I think we're back in Clarkdale.

00:21:08.094 --> 00:21:11.233
That's crazy. We just hopped in
we popped out Bob. Two seconds.

00:21:11.300 --> 00:21:13.643
A different country, sovereign nation.

00:21:13.710 --> 00:21:17.186
And then you can see new
tract homes right outside of it.

00:21:17.253 --> 00:21:19.486
Yeah those are $400,000 homes, easy.

00:21:19.553 --> 00:21:20.436
Probably.

00:21:23.138 --> 00:21:25.366
[Peter] Alright so Jerome. Next stop.

00:21:25.433 --> 00:21:27.786
[Bob] Alright. And now the drama begins.

00:21:28.350 --> 00:21:31.798
You're gonna hear this truck now
because of these hills.

00:21:31.865 --> 00:21:34.119
It's a lot easier going up
than coming down.

00:21:34.186 --> 00:21:35.353
It's gonna be hairy.

00:21:35.747 --> 00:21:38.369
So Bob what do you love
about being on the road?

00:21:38.436 --> 00:21:40.136
I love just driving.

00:21:40.857 --> 00:21:42.844
I love to drive and see areas.

00:21:42.911 --> 00:21:46.227
And this year I'm spending
more time in individual areas.

00:21:46.697 --> 00:21:48.856
I was a month in Death Valley.

00:21:48.923 --> 00:21:50.464
Almost a month at Organ Pipe.

00:21:50.936 --> 00:21:52.754
15 days in Boulder Oaks..

00:21:53.150 --> 00:21:56.333
I've been in Joshua Tree
and Coachella for a month.

00:21:56.400 --> 00:21:59.823
And it's great
because you really get to know the area.

00:22:00.216 --> 00:22:03.266
You can sort of get an idea
of what the area is actually like.

00:22:03.757 --> 00:22:06.486
How do you feel about
your fellow Americans?

00:22:06.553 --> 00:22:08.193
It's still a great country.

00:22:08.260 --> 00:22:09.639
If you want to work hard

00:22:10.077 --> 00:22:14.500
and it gets harder every year but if
you want to work hard it's great country.

00:22:14.567 --> 00:22:19.604
And I've met some people recently
who really work hard and they're happy.

00:22:20.024 --> 00:22:24.450
Having lots and lots of money,
and making it, and being a billionaire,

00:22:25.494 --> 00:22:26.668
I mean it must be great,

00:22:26.735 --> 00:22:30.489
but I meet a lot of people
who don't have much that seem happy.

00:22:31.080 --> 00:22:35.398
That doesn't mean there isn't hardship
and there aren't people having problems,

00:22:35.465 --> 00:22:38.724
but the story
that we're being told of people

00:22:39.640 --> 00:22:41.984
on social media is not real.

00:22:42.931 --> 00:22:43.970
-Yeah I agree.

00:22:44.037 --> 00:22:46.508
The real world is people are pretty great.

00:22:47.780 --> 00:22:50.682
I'm just so tired of
the "negativitay" my brother.

00:22:50.749 --> 00:22:52.554
-Yeah, I feel ya.

00:22:53.054 --> 00:22:56.017
On social media
about how people supposedly are.

00:22:56.402 --> 00:22:58.734
Well you know
because you're on social media,

00:22:58.801 --> 00:23:01.215
that's the business model
that works really well.

00:23:01.282 --> 00:23:04.428
My experience has been
that people are pretty great

00:23:04.495 --> 00:23:06.218
regardless of where you meet them.

00:23:06.285 --> 00:23:09.823
That's why I like spending more time
in these individual places.

00:23:09.890 --> 00:23:10.773
[Western music]

00:23:20.430 --> 00:23:23.059
[Peter] It's just built
right into the mountain here.

00:23:23.126 --> 00:23:24.540
Got the big J above.

00:23:24.607 --> 00:23:26.887
Up on the hillside there,
the biggest building,

00:23:26.954 --> 00:23:29.586
I believe was an infirmary.

00:23:29.653 --> 00:23:31.362
I think so. Now it's a hotel.

00:23:31.429 --> 00:23:33.982
Yeah we can stop by.
It's haunted so I've heard.

00:23:34.049 --> 00:23:34.932
-I'm sure it is.

00:23:35.510 --> 00:23:36.831
It's gonna get narrow Bob.

00:23:36.898 --> 00:23:38.154
Watch that wall.

00:23:38.221 --> 00:23:40.023
Just gotta keep me away from that wall.

00:23:40.090 --> 00:23:41.166
-You got room.

00:23:41.650 --> 00:23:45.053
But you get to listen to the truck.
That's the good thing.

00:23:45.120 --> 00:23:46.896
You like that sound Bob. Love it.

00:23:47.290 --> 00:23:49.819
-Just a lot of torque huh?
-A lot of torque.

00:23:54.598 --> 00:23:56.065
I can take all those spaces.

00:23:56.132 --> 00:23:58.833
I'll never turn around.
I'll have to back out which is…

00:23:58.900 --> 00:24:01.841
there's a multiple choice question
on the CDL test.

00:24:02.290 --> 00:24:06.214
When backing up…
and there's three different options.

00:24:06.281 --> 00:24:09.435
Have a person behind you.
Get out and look.

00:24:09.913 --> 00:24:11.790
And the last option is don't back up.

00:24:11.857 --> 00:24:13.328
That is the right answer.

00:24:13.922 --> 00:24:16.510
Don't back up.
Unless you absolutely have to.

00:24:17.190 --> 00:24:20.372
You gotta really watch me
on the right because this car is…

00:24:20.439 --> 00:24:22.204
-This is gonna be tough.
-Yeah.

00:24:22.730 --> 00:24:24.142
Okay you're good so far.

00:24:24.820 --> 00:24:26.130
-Okay. Thank you.

00:24:27.076 --> 00:24:28.501
I mean these trucks are big.

00:24:28.568 --> 00:24:30.215
-Lot of tourists here today.

00:24:30.911 --> 00:24:34.703
-Once the wickedest town in the West.
-A billion dollar. copper camp.

00:24:34.770 --> 00:24:36.755
[Peter] Mines closed, 1953.

00:24:37.222 --> 00:24:40.066
15,000 residents at its peak.

00:24:40.453 --> 00:24:42.500
You can see all the former tailings

00:24:42.567 --> 00:24:45.267
and evidence of
what went on here back in the day.

00:24:45.334 --> 00:24:48.004
Look at this massive slag pile.

00:24:48.071 --> 00:24:49.247
-I'm gonna park here.

00:24:50.520 --> 00:24:53.402
We'll let this thing
cool down for a little while.

00:24:58.692 --> 00:25:01.953
Look at all this machinery.
This is your fun park isn't it Bob?

00:25:02.020 --> 00:25:03.311
[Bob chuckles]

00:25:03.378 --> 00:25:07.043
Well I take a lot of pictures
of old beat up vehicles and stuff

00:25:07.110 --> 00:25:09.872
and it's amazing to see
what they did this work with.

00:25:10.360 --> 00:25:12.092
This was the top technology

00:25:12.159 --> 00:25:16.044
and I don't know if you ever watched
Jay Leno but he has an old Duesenberg

00:25:16.111 --> 00:25:19.962
and he talks about people
think these old cars are rickety and stuff

00:25:20.029 --> 00:25:21.693
but in most of the old cars,

00:25:21.760 --> 00:25:24.666
especially the '20s and '30s,
the technology worked.

00:25:25.076 --> 00:25:29.071
It would have represented the apex
of what we were capable of in those days.

00:25:29.138 --> 00:25:32.875
So it's fun to see the relics
because look at that bus.

00:25:33.238 --> 00:25:35.730
-Yeah, and the design was better back then.

00:25:35.797 --> 00:25:37.763
-Some of the relics are just beautiful.

00:25:37.830 --> 00:25:40.306
Look at that thing. That's an old Rambler.

00:25:40.373 --> 00:25:43.115
There's an old fire truck
if you're looking for one.

00:25:43.182 --> 00:25:44.243
That's…

00:25:44.310 --> 00:25:46.375
Before you Bob. Look at this setup.

00:25:46.442 --> 00:25:47.560
Look, there's my RV.

00:25:48.380 --> 00:25:50.556
Look at it with windows, paned windows.

00:25:51.760 --> 00:25:52.643
Shingles.

00:25:53.987 --> 00:25:56.353
[Peter] Look at that place.
Let's get up there.

00:25:57.280 --> 00:25:59.863
Hello. How is it in there? Did you go?

00:25:59.930 --> 00:26:02.744
Shop's so much fun.
Golly, I had a blast in there.

00:26:02.811 --> 00:26:04.947
-Oh cool.
-Enjoy if you go.

00:26:05.014 --> 00:26:05.897
Yeah thank you.

00:26:10.435 --> 00:26:12.115
[old timey music plays]

00:26:15.492 --> 00:26:17.319
-You like that one Bob?
-I love that.

00:26:17.386 --> 00:26:20.243
We're gonna have some drama
when we go over the mountain.

00:26:20.310 --> 00:26:22.543
-How you doing, ma'am?
-Good, how are you?

00:26:22.610 --> 00:26:23.635
…started this place.

00:26:23.702 --> 00:26:26.752
-Your mom and dad?
-Mm-hmm, Terry and Don Robertson.

00:26:26.819 --> 00:26:28.798
Okay so they were here in the heyday?

00:26:28.865 --> 00:26:30.817
-He came in the '80.

00:26:30.884 --> 00:26:31.767
-Oh okay.

00:26:31.834 --> 00:26:34.660
He was an Iowa farm boy
and they both actually met…

00:26:34.727 --> 00:26:36.309
Don's actually my stepdad.

00:26:36.376 --> 00:26:38.542
-Is that him right there?
-That is him.

00:26:38.609 --> 00:26:41.392
All the pictures you'll see,
he brought his old sawmill.

00:26:41.459 --> 00:26:44.687
It's a 1914 gas Witte engine
that runs a sawmill.

00:26:44.754 --> 00:26:45.637
Okay.

00:26:45.704 --> 00:26:47.846
So he was out there all the time.

00:26:47.913 --> 00:26:50.003
So this place is legendary a little bit?

00:26:50.070 --> 00:26:50.953
Pretty much.

00:26:51.020 --> 00:26:54.544
Gearheads come from all over the world
and they would just talk to him.

00:26:54.611 --> 00:26:57.527
-They love the classic stuff?
-They love the classic stuff.

00:26:57.594 --> 00:27:00.676
He has over a hundred
antique trucks and motorcycles and cars.

00:27:00.744 --> 00:27:02.052
Yeah the trucks are great.

00:27:02.119 --> 00:27:03.523
You're tied into this place?

00:27:03.590 --> 00:27:05.321
I am. I own it now.

00:27:05.388 --> 00:27:07.663
We love the lifestyle
living on the mountain.

00:27:07.730 --> 00:27:09.077
What's the lifestyle?

00:27:09.144 --> 00:27:13.721
You get to close the gate at night.
The government doesn't tell you what to do.

00:27:13.788 --> 00:27:15.903
And the country. Country lifestyle.

00:27:15.970 --> 00:27:18.296
You know what I mean.
Not a lot of regulations.

00:27:18.363 --> 00:27:19.983
-No Karens.
-No Karens.

00:27:20.050 --> 00:27:22.502
And we can do
what we want to do with the Karens.

00:27:22.569 --> 00:27:23.542
[Peter laughs]

00:27:23.609 --> 00:27:26.144
-You regulate Karens up here?
-Not in a bad way.

00:27:26.211 --> 00:27:27.094
Okay.

00:27:27.586 --> 00:27:29.613
-You let 'em know their place.
-Right.

00:27:29.680 --> 00:27:31.392
We live on the side of a mountain.

00:27:31.459 --> 00:27:34.356
It's up and down.
My house is way on top up there.

00:27:34.423 --> 00:27:36.496
-Up here?
-We love the lifestyle.

00:27:36.563 --> 00:27:37.446
That's cool.

00:27:37.513 --> 00:27:39.638
All of our grandchildren are homeschooled,

00:27:39.705 --> 00:27:42.306
all of them have trades,
already know what to do.

00:27:42.373 --> 00:27:45.101
My fourteen year old
already runs an excavator

00:27:45.168 --> 00:27:47.680
up and down the mountains and stuff.

00:27:47.747 --> 00:27:49.703
-Fourteen?
-Yeah he's fourteen.

00:27:49.770 --> 00:27:52.111
-All homeschooled?
-All homeschooled.

00:27:52.178 --> 00:27:55.387
-All staying around the area?
-They all know how to do something.

00:27:55.454 --> 00:27:56.840
Which is useful now.

00:27:56.907 --> 00:27:57.941
Exactly.

00:27:58.008 --> 00:28:00.658
-That's where the jobs are.
-They have skills. Right.

00:28:00.725 --> 00:28:02.604
Because we have no more skills.

00:28:02.671 --> 00:28:05.022
Everybody knows
how to press a button in Google.

00:28:05.089 --> 00:28:06.286
Do what I'm doing.

00:28:06.353 --> 00:28:08.133
And then they know everything.

00:28:08.200 --> 00:28:09.965
And then you try to hire them.

00:28:10.463 --> 00:28:14.215
I don't want to go there.
I don't want to tell you how that is!

00:28:14.728 --> 00:28:17.400
-They have to be taught some skills.
-It's true.

00:28:17.467 --> 00:28:19.533
You know, we're just old school.

00:28:19.600 --> 00:28:21.601
I'm coming from a really small town.

00:28:21.668 --> 00:28:23.654
Actually I was from Louisiana.

00:28:23.721 --> 00:28:25.497
I was raised in the bayous.

00:28:25.564 --> 00:28:26.780
-No way.
-Yeah.

00:28:27.270 --> 00:28:30.224
When you come from Louisiana
to somewhere like Arizona

00:28:30.291 --> 00:28:33.143
then you find out
how Arizona is so diversified.

00:28:33.210 --> 00:28:35.110
Every hundred miles there's something.

00:28:35.177 --> 00:28:38.182
-We've been talking about that.
-It's beautiful.

00:28:38.249 --> 00:28:42.319
If you land in Phoenix you're like,
what the hell do people do here?

00:28:42.386 --> 00:28:43.694
That's a good question.

00:28:43.761 --> 00:28:45.168
Well they stay inside.

00:28:45.235 --> 00:28:48.434
-That's what they do.
-So we're making a video on that today.

00:28:48.871 --> 00:28:51.203
We're going granular
in this part of Arizona.

00:28:51.270 --> 00:28:53.333
-And every town is totally different.
-Right.

00:28:53.400 --> 00:28:56.673
-It's old school Americana.
-It is and that's what you try to preserve.

00:28:56.740 --> 00:28:58.963
And that was what my stepdad was all about.

00:28:59.030 --> 00:29:01.933
Don, he just loved the United States.

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:04.976
And he loved what it was about.
He loved the freedom he had.

00:29:05.043 --> 00:29:07.414
And he loved the industrial part of it.

00:29:07.481 --> 00:29:10.693
And showing how it evolved and stuff.

00:29:10.760 --> 00:29:12.894
-You're still getting that up here?

00:29:12.961 --> 00:29:15.523
Oh yeah. People come all over.
They just love it.

00:29:15.590 --> 00:29:20.173
You know Elon is here with an electric car
but we have a 1902 electric Studebaker.

00:29:20.240 --> 00:29:22.426
It wasn't a bright idea.

00:29:22.493 --> 00:29:24.463
We had electric cars 100 years ago.

00:29:24.530 --> 00:29:26.595
-Can we go see that?
-It wasn't the first.

00:29:26.662 --> 00:29:28.523
Yeah you pay your admission.

00:29:28.590 --> 00:29:31.303
-[Bob laughs]
You're not getting in there for free.

00:29:31.370 --> 00:29:32.838
-This is your granddad.
-Yeah.

00:29:32.905 --> 00:29:35.673
-And I was just talking to your mom.
-Yeah.

00:29:35.740 --> 00:29:37.117
Oh that's the electric one.

00:29:37.184 --> 00:29:39.834
Yeah so this is a 1902 electric car.

00:29:40.433 --> 00:29:42.563
It was called a Studebaker Roundabout.

00:29:42.630 --> 00:29:45.806
If you were a gentleman
in the day mobbing one of these

00:29:46.310 --> 00:29:49.138
you would have been
heavily sought after with the ladies.

00:29:49.205 --> 00:29:53.066
It had no combustion so they weren't
annoyed from all the engine noise.

00:29:53.133 --> 00:29:54.700
You know it wasn't all racket.

00:29:55.110 --> 00:29:58.044
You could take a nice quiet ride
and talk to your woman.

00:29:58.111 --> 00:30:00.011
-And didn't have to worry about horses.

00:30:00.078 --> 00:30:02.808
-The horses, and the smell, and the flies.

00:30:02.875 --> 00:30:05.689
The only problem is it didn't go very far.

00:30:05.756 --> 00:30:08.390
without having to be
recharged again so combustion…

00:30:09.040 --> 00:30:12.329
Well that turned into a plus
when you were talking about the date.

00:30:12.396 --> 00:30:13.455
-Yeah.
-[chuckling]

00:30:14.629 --> 00:30:15.739
[Peter] There you go, Bob.

00:30:16.781 --> 00:30:18.043
Mic drop Bob.

00:30:18.110 --> 00:30:19.501
This collapses down.

00:30:20.090 --> 00:30:22.219
-What about the battery setup?

00:30:22.286 --> 00:30:25.031
So it's all under here
in this compartment.

00:30:25.098 --> 00:30:27.403
So that battery technology
was there back then?

00:30:27.470 --> 00:30:30.017
Yeah 48 volts. It would have looked like…

00:30:30.769 --> 00:30:32.273
-Right here.
-Okay.

00:30:33.770 --> 00:30:37.348
So now we modernized it,
put 48 volt system in but it still works.

00:30:37.415 --> 00:30:40.603
It's got the original
Westinghouse electric motor on it.

00:30:40.670 --> 00:30:43.253
-Why was there such a gap

00:30:43.320 --> 00:30:45.573
between electric cars then and now?

00:30:45.640 --> 00:30:49.158
-I mean electric cars have really…
-Combustion just dominated.

00:30:49.225 --> 00:30:52.631
You can see they have problems
with the freezing weather

00:30:52.698 --> 00:30:54.254
and them catching on fire

00:30:54.321 --> 00:30:57.412
and trying to find
a plug-in station somewhere.

00:30:57.796 --> 00:30:59.649
When you go to take it to a mechanic,

00:30:59.716 --> 00:31:02.731
everything is high voltage
so it's extremely dangerous.

00:31:02.798 --> 00:31:04.455
You gotta know what you're doing.

00:31:04.522 --> 00:31:07.046
I think there's just
so many discrepancies where

00:31:07.113 --> 00:31:09.589
modern combustion has come so far

00:31:10.136 --> 00:31:11.469
and hasn't stopped.

00:31:11.940 --> 00:31:16.536
But yeah, so this is
Don's '28 Studebaker race car.

00:31:16.603 --> 00:31:18.043
He actually raced this.

00:31:18.110 --> 00:31:21.458
He took the straight 8
out of a Studebaker school bus

00:31:21.525 --> 00:31:22.637
and put it in here.

00:31:22.704 --> 00:31:24.283
And this thing still works.

00:31:24.350 --> 00:31:26.542
We took this out
for the 4th of July parade

00:31:26.609 --> 00:31:29.419
and I was driving
with my daughter so it was pretty cool.

00:31:29.493 --> 00:31:33.787
-So your granddad was a wild man.
-Yeah he was a little bit of a wild man.

00:31:34.260 --> 00:31:38.490
This is the original structure,
that house, when this was a mining camp.

00:31:38.557 --> 00:31:40.171
[Bob] How did he get this place?

00:31:40.238 --> 00:31:42.192
He came up on his own intuition

00:31:42.259 --> 00:31:46.374
and said I need a place with
four seasons of weather and mining history.

00:31:46.441 --> 00:31:48.587
Because he was just a mining guru man.

00:31:48.654 --> 00:31:50.733
He loved collecting old parts.

00:31:50.800 --> 00:31:53.358
So you're not gonna be able
to probably fathom this

00:31:53.425 --> 00:31:55.083
but nothing was here.

00:31:55.550 --> 00:31:58.176
This is his 1914 sawmill.

00:31:58.243 --> 00:32:00.437
Don brought his sweet little baby up here.

00:32:00.504 --> 00:32:03.357
So it's a 1914 Witte. It's 30 horsepower.

00:32:03.930 --> 00:32:08.269
Back in the day when this was a little town
that was a minor league baseball field.

00:32:08.336 --> 00:32:10.812
-Minor league baseball field right there?
-Yep.

00:32:11.330 --> 00:32:13.959
So your granddad
brought all of this up here?

00:32:14.026 --> 00:32:16.741
All of this stuff up here
that you see, yeah.

00:32:16.808 --> 00:32:20.772
So how what was his economic engine?
How did he…

00:32:20.839 --> 00:32:24.446
So he was a mechanical engineer,
and mechanical operator,

00:32:25.030 --> 00:32:27.459
and heavy equipment operator, truck driver,

00:32:27.526 --> 00:32:30.253
all into one package for the union.

00:32:30.320 --> 00:32:33.692
It's funny 'cause we're from
the same union. I was a crane operator.

00:32:33.759 --> 00:32:37.432
He took all of his time that he had been
working with them and on the side

00:32:37.499 --> 00:32:39.773
he had been collecting, and collecting.

00:32:39.840 --> 00:32:42.401
Wanted to get away from
working for the man.

00:32:42.468 --> 00:32:45.847
Finally got to a point where he thought
he could reveal enough stuff

00:32:45.914 --> 00:32:47.313
to make this place cool

00:32:47.380 --> 00:32:49.509
and then charge a little two dollar fee

00:32:50.101 --> 00:32:53.685
and he hustled wood on the side.

00:32:53.752 --> 00:32:56.576
So the reason why
that saw mill is so significant

00:32:57.100 --> 00:32:59.886
is because he would
hustle his wood on the side.

00:32:59.953 --> 00:33:02.637
Because he was trying to generate people.
No Internet.

00:33:02.704 --> 00:33:05.722
-She said it ran every day.
-It used to run every single day.

00:33:05.789 --> 00:33:08.043
Where else are you gonna get wood milled?

00:33:08.110 --> 00:33:09.783
This is their house up here.

00:33:10.263 --> 00:33:12.663
-That's your mom's house?
-That's my mom's house.

00:33:12.730 --> 00:33:14.617
-Oh that's sick.
-We did all the…

00:33:14.684 --> 00:33:16.138
Way up there!

00:33:16.205 --> 00:33:19.981
So we used that 1914 mill
to cut a lot of the lumber for that house.

00:33:20.944 --> 00:33:22.762
-That is sweet.
-It turned out slick.

00:33:22.829 --> 00:33:24.203
I mean look at their view.

00:33:24.270 --> 00:33:26.870
-She's looking all the way out to Sedona.
-Yeah.

00:33:27.310 --> 00:33:30.045
So your mom was talking about
her grandkids

00:33:30.112 --> 00:33:31.986
moving machinery around at 14.

00:33:32.053 --> 00:33:34.499
-Yeah my son.
-Like know how to do everything.

00:33:34.566 --> 00:33:37.489
They're all home schooled,
hands on practical application.

00:33:37.556 --> 00:33:40.556
Ten years ago that would have been
looked at as the bad play.

00:33:40.623 --> 00:33:44.368
And now it's like everyone's like,
"Yeah those are the jobs."

00:33:44.435 --> 00:33:46.397
Those are the jobs that you want to do.

00:33:46.464 --> 00:33:50.197
Everybody's trying to see in the contrast
of you go to college, get in debt,

00:33:50.264 --> 00:33:53.329
and then they're like well why is Joe Smith

00:33:53.396 --> 00:33:55.403
working his trade for four or five years

00:33:55.470 --> 00:33:58.233
and pulling in 150k debt free?

00:33:58.300 --> 00:34:00.865
So because your grandfather

00:34:00.932 --> 00:34:05.741
took that super risky adventurous
step in life, you're living this life.

00:34:05.808 --> 00:34:09.714
Your kids are living
this really rogue hands on life.

00:34:10.136 --> 00:34:11.608
-Yeah.
-That's pretty awesome.

00:34:11.675 --> 00:34:13.450
Yeah, it is cool, man.

00:34:14.310 --> 00:34:18.160
We tried the public school system
and I'm not knocking every public school.

00:34:18.227 --> 00:34:20.686
I mean there's good educational places

00:34:20.753 --> 00:34:23.845
but you have control of
how you're teaching your kids

00:34:23.912 --> 00:34:27.609
and there's a stigma that it's like
they're not social

00:34:27.676 --> 00:34:29.912
they're lacking and it's…

00:34:30.520 --> 00:34:31.712
It's really untrue.

00:34:31.779 --> 00:34:35.970
I mean they're heavily integrated
with FFA, their church group.

00:34:36.450 --> 00:34:37.640
They do co-ops.

00:34:37.707 --> 00:34:40.317
Most of these guys
on the other side of the mountain.

00:34:40.384 --> 00:34:44.749
Home cooking baked goods, jujitsu,
weight lifting, some form of martial arts.

00:34:44.816 --> 00:34:46.153
Just cool stuff.

00:34:46.220 --> 00:34:49.682
This two story building
was the original house

00:34:49.749 --> 00:34:53.045
that was used by the miners
in the late 1800s.

00:34:53.112 --> 00:34:55.056
This is the only original structure

00:34:55.782 --> 00:34:57.435
that was on the property.

00:34:57.502 --> 00:35:00.208
This, and the shafts that they went down.

00:35:00.950 --> 00:35:03.148
1907 to 1959

00:35:03.215 --> 00:35:06.541
a lady named Petra
actually lived in this house by herself.

00:35:07.283 --> 00:35:09.218
She lived to be 105 years old.

00:35:09.285 --> 00:35:12.457
So her last three years
she moved to Prescott and passed there.

00:35:12.524 --> 00:35:15.699
But yeah you can imagine
she's going out to get all her own wood

00:35:15.766 --> 00:35:18.972
'cause there's no electricity.
So she's trying to heat her house,

00:35:19.039 --> 00:35:20.936
make her food all by herself.

00:35:21.003 --> 00:35:22.484
-You're talking 105.
-105?

00:35:22.551 --> 00:35:24.153
-That's why.
-That's why.

00:35:24.220 --> 00:35:26.632
What's your take on this part of Arizona?

00:35:27.310 --> 00:35:29.528
I love the Wild Wild West man. I mean…

00:35:29.595 --> 00:35:31.959
-It still feels that way huh?
-Yeah this is…

00:35:32.350 --> 00:35:35.183
This time period right here
is pure debauchery.

00:35:35.250 --> 00:35:37.903
Las Vegas
without any law enforcement you know.

00:35:37.970 --> 00:35:40.374
Jerome was deemed
the Wickedest Town In The West.

00:35:40.441 --> 00:35:42.063
-It was Las Vegas without law.

00:35:42.130 --> 00:35:43.435
Without law, you know?

00:35:43.502 --> 00:35:45.841
-So just brothels, gun fights…

00:35:45.908 --> 00:35:49.910
That whole strip that you guys came through
in Jerome was all red light district.

00:35:49.977 --> 00:35:51.961
So the women weren't allowed to mine.

00:35:52.028 --> 00:35:55.287
So they had to come up with
their own form of currency.

00:35:55.354 --> 00:35:56.766
So they opened brothels.

00:35:57.374 --> 00:35:59.480
And it was just the whole Wild West of it.

00:35:59.547 --> 00:36:03.064
Then you had people from Spain coming,
people from China coming.

00:36:03.131 --> 00:36:04.881
So China brought the opium dens.

00:36:05.315 --> 00:36:07.445
Then you had prohibition
with the alcohols.

00:36:07.512 --> 00:36:09.756
So that was a high commodity with drinking.

00:36:09.823 --> 00:36:12.752
So you got opium and alcohol
mixed in with prostitution.

00:36:12.819 --> 00:36:14.119
Now you got mining.

00:36:14.186 --> 00:36:15.448
I mean it's just madness.

00:36:15.515 --> 00:36:17.843
-A ton of money coming through?
-Ton of money.

00:36:17.910 --> 00:36:20.187
-And not people you can push around.
-No.

00:36:20.254 --> 00:36:22.861
And that's the thing.
And the women were headstrong.

00:36:22.928 --> 00:36:26.352
I mean the guys started getting out
of place, they'd just shoot them.

00:36:26.419 --> 00:36:28.256
Throw them down a shaft.

00:36:28.755 --> 00:36:30.109
That's just the way it was.

00:36:30.176 --> 00:36:32.993
When did that stop?
Like when was the last year of that?

00:36:33.060 --> 00:36:36.142
They started civilizing
more into the early '20s.

00:36:36.566 --> 00:36:39.570
And then through the '20s to the '50s,

00:36:40.064 --> 00:36:42.523
they had a fire department,
they had sheriffs.

00:36:42.590 --> 00:36:46.448
-So early 20's, so we're talking
basically a hundred years ago.

00:36:46.515 --> 00:36:48.225
-Yes.
-Where it was just wild.

00:36:48.292 --> 00:36:49.175
Yep.

00:36:49.831 --> 00:36:52.362
Just be careful in here.
This is a little sketch.

00:36:52.429 --> 00:36:53.312
Here we go.

00:36:54.251 --> 00:36:57.001
[Peter] This was the mannequin
from one of the brothels?

00:36:57.068 --> 00:36:58.374
Yeah. [laughs]

00:36:59.670 --> 00:37:00.615
Some of the beds.

00:37:00.682 --> 00:37:02.943
And you guys
haven't done anything here right?

00:37:03.010 --> 00:37:04.657
-No. We just kind of left it.

00:37:06.173 --> 00:37:09.546
-This wood, if someone weighs a lot
they're going through this floor.

00:37:09.613 --> 00:37:12.428
Yeah I just had a crew
through here yesterday so we're…

00:37:12.495 --> 00:37:14.095
Oh look at the old wooden stove.

00:37:14.170 --> 00:37:16.463
-Yeah her old wooden stove.
-Oh that is cool.

00:37:16.530 --> 00:37:17.499
Old chimney.

00:37:18.030 --> 00:37:21.911
-Are you glad you're in 2026 or do you wish
you were growing up back then?

00:37:22.540 --> 00:37:24.673
I'd have to say probably back then.

00:37:24.740 --> 00:37:27.181
It's kind of the same old demons

00:37:27.807 --> 00:37:29.631
but just modernized technology.

00:37:30.370 --> 00:37:31.932
-That's a good way of saying it.

00:37:31.999 --> 00:37:34.628
Phones are a great thing to have
but they're also…

00:37:34.695 --> 00:37:36.118
they can be very dangerous.

00:37:36.753 --> 00:37:40.388
Some of the things that we're exposed to
so rapidly in today's society

00:37:40.456 --> 00:37:41.786
is pretty dangerous.

00:37:41.853 --> 00:37:44.619
Making a phone call
to see how someone's doing

00:37:44.686 --> 00:37:46.671
is a lost art in a lot of ways.

00:37:46.738 --> 00:37:47.621
-That's true.

00:37:47.688 --> 00:37:50.496
Just simple things
where you went to the store

00:37:50.563 --> 00:37:53.744
and your hardwood guy and your dentist

00:37:53.811 --> 00:37:56.532
was probably someone
you knew well, and their kids,

00:37:56.599 --> 00:37:58.731
and their reputation, and their character.

00:37:58.798 --> 00:38:01.098
Now it's just who's the best?
Can fix me quick?

00:38:02.807 --> 00:38:04.303
Can I just get in and out.

00:38:04.867 --> 00:38:08.114
-Bob and I were talking about this
on the way up to Jerome,

00:38:08.516 --> 00:38:10.916
in Unit 11 which you can see out there.

00:38:10.983 --> 00:38:12.823
If you can look out this window.

00:38:13.245 --> 00:38:14.213
Oh cool man.

00:38:14.280 --> 00:38:19.351
We were talking about the Internet is
creating a false story about the country.

00:38:19.885 --> 00:38:23.200
Because when you get out
in the country like Bob does, like I do,

00:38:23.705 --> 00:38:26.619
the vast majority of people
are cool and open.

00:38:27.134 --> 00:38:29.696
Today we'd run into people
that want to talk to us.

00:38:29.763 --> 00:38:31.675
-And great stories.
-Great stories.

00:38:31.742 --> 00:38:33.208
You're a great story.

00:38:33.275 --> 00:38:37.743
And then you get online
and it just looks like division and chaos.

00:38:37.810 --> 00:38:39.111
And pure dopamine.

00:38:39.178 --> 00:38:40.841
I think you're absolutely right.

00:38:40.908 --> 00:38:44.143
I visited my sister in Baytown, Texas.

00:38:44.210 --> 00:38:47.383
It's exactly what you're saying.
I was up in Sidney, Montana.

00:38:47.450 --> 00:38:50.941
I mean the little cafe
had the local's coffee mugs

00:38:51.008 --> 00:38:52.531
with their names on the shelf.

00:38:52.598 --> 00:38:54.980
And it was like this is cool.
This is down home.

00:38:55.047 --> 00:38:58.057
You know that
if something happens in the street

00:38:58.124 --> 00:39:01.194
and someone gets hurt
that whole restaurant is gonna empty out

00:39:01.261 --> 00:39:04.976
and be like what's going on?
How can I help? How can I be of service?

00:39:05.042 --> 00:39:07.315
That's a lost thing.
But no, I agree with you.

00:39:07.382 --> 00:39:09.679
There is a thing that's portrayed

00:39:10.230 --> 00:39:11.773
and it's sad to see.

00:39:11.840 --> 00:39:13.401
'Cause we feed off of it.

00:39:13.468 --> 00:39:17.397
-And if young people, say,
don't have time on the road traveling

00:39:17.890 --> 00:39:21.405
in front of the screens,
they believe that might be the reality.

00:39:21.472 --> 00:39:23.292
A lot of people. That's the problem.

00:39:23.359 --> 00:39:26.558
You're interacting with people.
People are pumped to be here.

00:39:26.625 --> 00:39:30.388
And typically I try to keep it that way.
It's a very family friendly place.

00:39:30.455 --> 00:39:32.660
I try to entertain the people
in the sense of

00:39:32.727 --> 00:39:34.794
I don't want to be daunting and

00:39:34.861 --> 00:39:37.977
how are you guys doing
and wherever you're from.

00:39:38.044 --> 00:39:40.786
If they want to talk about it
then I'll let them.

00:39:40.853 --> 00:39:43.348
-I brought all this stuff up. Thank you.

00:39:43.415 --> 00:39:46.753
This is how we learn.
This is what I do. You saw my videos.

00:39:46.820 --> 00:39:49.001
It's like we went into a portal in here.

00:39:49.068 --> 00:39:52.332
Yeah. They hit over $2 billion
in copper in that time.

00:39:52.399 --> 00:39:54.425
They were using a lot of it for the war.

00:39:54.492 --> 00:39:58.634
For World War I
they were building artillery with copper.

00:39:59.460 --> 00:40:01.867
[Peter] What's the story?
This was for the house?

00:40:01.934 --> 00:40:03.127
-Yeah. Outhouse.

00:40:03.194 --> 00:40:04.908
-But why way up here?

00:40:04.975 --> 00:40:06.547
-See all these rocks?

00:40:07.130 --> 00:40:09.009
These were all stacked by hand.

00:40:09.570 --> 00:40:12.840
These were all old foundations.
The housing was up here.

00:40:12.907 --> 00:40:16.615
All the production for the mining
would have been on this flat ground.

00:40:16.682 --> 00:40:19.817
There was up to 300 people
living up here at once.

00:40:19.884 --> 00:40:21.793
That's called the Haines Shaft.

00:40:21.860 --> 00:40:24.768
This was a suburb of Arizona
called Haines, Arizona.

00:40:24.835 --> 00:40:26.603
Had its own little post office.

00:40:26.670 --> 00:40:29.563
Different prospector with money
investing in his own copper.

00:40:29.630 --> 00:40:31.474
Bob and I are just blazing through today.

00:40:31.541 --> 00:40:35.133
But any one of those towns
we could spend a full day in easily.

00:40:35.200 --> 00:40:37.133
-It's kind of a little hidden gem.

00:40:37.200 --> 00:40:39.612
This is what it's like hiking in Arizona.

00:40:39.679 --> 00:40:41.274
[laughter]

00:40:41.750 --> 00:40:42.980
-That's right.

00:40:43.047 --> 00:40:45.833
-This is one of your kids?
-Yeah this is Kaden.

00:40:45.900 --> 00:40:46.953
My 14 year old.

00:40:47.020 --> 00:40:49.685
Kaden, nice. Eye contact firm shake.

00:40:49.752 --> 00:40:52.743
-Nice Kaden. You taught him well.
-This is his dog, Remy.

00:40:52.810 --> 00:40:54.816
Kaden what are you working on right now?

00:40:54.883 --> 00:40:57.670
Trying to get the 1943 KB International.

00:40:58.424 --> 00:40:59.843
-Just get it running?
-Yeah.

00:40:59.910 --> 00:41:02.163
-You know how to fix those things?
-Yeah.

00:41:02.230 --> 00:41:03.893
-What's the belt here?

00:41:03.960 --> 00:41:06.303
This is a buckle I got made in New Mexico.

00:41:06.370 --> 00:41:08.883
It's the Gold Key Mine.

00:41:08.950 --> 00:41:11.874
And then I got my initials
and then Romans 8:28.

00:41:11.941 --> 00:41:14.985
-This is his own branding
that he's trying to come out with.

00:41:15.058 --> 00:41:15.985
-The KL?

00:41:16.052 --> 00:41:18.456
-Yeah the KL for Kaden Lefeu.

00:41:18.523 --> 00:41:20.782
-Nice. You love it up here?

00:41:20.849 --> 00:41:21.732
Oh yeah.

00:41:22.216 --> 00:41:24.847
-You keeping busy? Never bored?

00:41:24.914 --> 00:41:25.828
Never.

00:41:25.895 --> 00:41:28.403
He's either doing carpentry,

00:41:28.809 --> 00:41:31.018
running an excavator backhoe,

00:41:31.507 --> 00:41:32.884
shooting squirrels.

00:41:32.951 --> 00:41:35.463
-Excavator?
-I mean it's just kind of endless.

00:41:35.530 --> 00:41:37.705
-[Bob] Where's the truck?
-Riding motocross.

00:41:37.772 --> 00:41:40.293
You want to see the truck?
The truck's pretty rad.

00:41:43.775 --> 00:41:46.246
The battery's dead
needs a new fuel filter.

00:41:47.110 --> 00:41:49.225
We've been trying to find the keys for it.

00:41:49.292 --> 00:41:52.112
The electrical's a little chewed up
but it's almost done.

00:41:52.179 --> 00:41:54.683
I want to drive it
in the parade 4th of July.

00:41:54.750 --> 00:41:56.773
[Bob] Is this an old army truck?

00:41:57.433 --> 00:41:59.273
It got painted but yeah it was a…

00:41:59.340 --> 00:42:01.823
-Yeah, it was an old military truck.
-US Navy.

00:42:01.890 --> 00:42:05.130
The front axle,
that's definitely a military axle.

00:42:05.760 --> 00:42:07.896
With the ball peen front joints.

00:42:07.963 --> 00:42:10.731
[Peter] Kaden, you got
buddies doing the same thing?

00:42:10.798 --> 00:42:11.681
-Hm-mm.
-No?

00:42:12.169 --> 00:42:13.176
Brothers?

00:42:13.243 --> 00:42:15.141
-Yeah I got 5 siblings.
-There you go.

00:42:15.700 --> 00:42:18.101
-That's all you need.
-[Bob] This thing is solid.

00:42:18.168 --> 00:42:19.756
Yeah isn't this thing wild?

00:42:22.042 --> 00:42:24.292
This thing runs.
You want to hear it fired up?

00:42:24.359 --> 00:42:25.830
-Let's do it.
-Absolutely.

00:42:27.121 --> 00:42:28.152
[spray can hissing]

00:42:28.219 --> 00:42:29.102
Oh.

00:42:29.501 --> 00:42:32.187
[engine cranks and starts]

00:42:33.491 --> 00:42:35.171
[diesel engine rumbling]

00:42:41.619 --> 00:42:44.245
[engine revving]

00:42:52.700 --> 00:42:56.773
-[Peter] You have a blacksmith here?
-Yeah we have a Blacksmith working here.

00:42:56.840 --> 00:42:58.063
-This is Mr. William.

00:42:58.130 --> 00:43:00.914
He Blacksmiths and he does woodwork.

00:43:00.981 --> 00:43:02.334
[Peter] Oh that's cool.

00:43:02.746 --> 00:43:05.412
He makes these
handmade peppercorn grinders and…

00:43:05.879 --> 00:43:10.253
Yeah. So he's got his coal forge back there
and he pretty much uses this propane guy

00:43:10.320 --> 00:43:13.183
so he can adjust his heat
whenever he wants

00:43:13.250 --> 00:43:14.916
and it's not so temperamental.

00:43:15.397 --> 00:43:19.683
And we've got a fire ban going
so you can't run the coal forge very well.

00:43:19.750 --> 00:43:22.823
Is there many people
doing your craft anymore or not really?

00:43:22.890 --> 00:43:28.258
There has been a big resurgence
since those shows like Forged in Fire.

00:43:28.325 --> 00:43:29.208
-Okay.

00:43:29.876 --> 00:43:32.960
You get a lot of people
that want to try it again

00:43:33.027 --> 00:43:35.159
and make knives and make a…

00:43:36.260 --> 00:43:38.065
Everybody wants to be a knife maker.

00:43:38.132 --> 00:43:39.747
-Damascus steel?
-Yep

00:43:40.300 --> 00:43:42.343
-That's a buzzword, Bob.
-Is it?

00:43:42.410 --> 00:43:43.526
In the knife industry.

00:43:43.593 --> 00:43:46.300
-I'm not a knife man.
-Me neither.

00:43:47.220 --> 00:43:49.299
I made that back in the '90s.

00:43:49.986 --> 00:43:51.483
'95 I think it was.

00:43:51.972 --> 00:43:52.855
My uncle.

00:43:53.510 --> 00:43:55.419
used to hate going into restaurants

00:43:55.486 --> 00:43:57.909
and getting those steak knives
that are like…

00:43:58.955 --> 00:44:00.477
-Don't cut anything.
-Right.

00:44:01.060 --> 00:44:04.119
So he always carried his own.
So I made this for him.

00:44:04.644 --> 00:44:07.223
And you can see
the different layers and everything.

00:44:07.297 --> 00:44:10.326
I made that for him.
He carried it until he passed away.

00:44:10.393 --> 00:44:14.569
And then I got it back. So I keep that
up here just to show people I do…

00:44:15.368 --> 00:44:18.173
-So he'd go into the restaurant
with his own steak knife?

00:44:18.240 --> 00:44:19.514
He would bring his own.

00:44:19.581 --> 00:44:22.331
-I like it.
-[Bob] I'm not using your cheap knife.

00:44:22.398 --> 00:44:23.281
[chuckling]

00:44:25.251 --> 00:44:28.070
-Take care. All the best. 
-Thank you.

00:44:32.300 --> 00:44:34.877
[Peter] I'll owe you money.
I don't expect freebies.

00:44:34.944 --> 00:44:36.103
Can we get a picture?

00:44:36.170 --> 00:44:39.111
-How much do I owe you? You sure?
-Yeah we're good.

00:44:39.980 --> 00:44:42.764
-It's actually video right now.
-Who are you guys?

00:44:42.831 --> 00:44:46.205
I'll tell you guys when he leaves.

00:44:47.142 --> 00:44:48.322
There you go.

00:44:48.389 --> 00:44:50.630
-Sweet.
-[Bob] Thank you. Really fun.

00:44:50.697 --> 00:44:51.867
Love what you got here.

00:44:51.934 --> 00:44:54.295
I want to tell people,
what's your place called?

00:44:54.362 --> 00:44:56.503
-Gold King Mine.
-Gold King Mine.

00:44:56.570 --> 00:44:59.913
So if they're coming up to Jerome,
drive from the fire station.

00:44:59.980 --> 00:45:03.243
One mile past the fire station,
the Gold King Mine Ghost Town.

00:45:03.310 --> 00:45:04.688
We almost missed out on it.

00:45:04.755 --> 00:45:05.638
I know man.

00:45:05.705 --> 00:45:09.236
We almost turned around,
that woulda sucked. So thank you.

00:45:09.303 --> 00:45:10.766
There it is guys.

00:45:10.833 --> 00:45:12.214
You come up this road here.

00:45:12.281 --> 00:45:14.613
-It's all self-guided.
-Self-guided, okay.

00:45:14.680 --> 00:45:17.580
I'm gonna fire it up.
Bob wants to fire it up for you guys.

00:45:17.647 --> 00:45:19.853
-He wants to impress you.
-[laughter]

00:45:19.920 --> 00:45:23.175
It almost sounds like a Prius that's angry.

00:45:24.050 --> 00:45:24.933
See you guys.

00:45:27.560 --> 00:45:29.925
-[Bob] Look at that.
-[Peter] That is beautiful.

00:45:29.992 --> 00:45:31.894
I was just thinking going into Jerome.

00:45:31.961 --> 00:45:35.278
Let's check it out.
I know a cool place. I've been here before.

00:45:36.720 --> 00:45:39.884
Didn't he say this part right here
is the red light district?

00:45:39.951 --> 00:45:41.668
I think it's up here.

00:45:41.735 --> 00:45:42.843
Let's check it out.

00:45:42.910 --> 00:45:46.543
-[Peter] It's got a cool feel to it.
-[Bob] I think it's a cool place.

00:45:46.610 --> 00:45:48.669
I love these old post offices, Bob.

00:45:49.150 --> 00:45:50.547
You ever go into these?

00:45:50.614 --> 00:45:52.853
-I love the way they smell.
-Yeah, right.

00:45:53.951 --> 00:45:55.491
With the old metal boxes.

00:45:56.025 --> 00:45:58.993
Small town like this.
They're open for a couple hours a day.

00:45:59.060 --> 00:46:01.589
Look at these old boxes.
All the old detail.

00:46:02.941 --> 00:46:04.660
-Whoa.
-So cool.

00:46:04.727 --> 00:46:05.751
Look at that.

00:46:05.818 --> 00:46:08.218
I know you're more interested
in prostitutes Bob.

00:46:08.285 --> 00:46:09.168
[Bob laughs]

00:46:10.518 --> 00:46:12.671
-From the 1840s.
-I think it's up here.

00:46:12.738 --> 00:46:14.373
Okay here it is I think.

00:46:14.440 --> 00:46:17.664
This building was originally
a brothel known as Jennie's Place.

00:46:17.731 --> 00:46:19.629
It was built in 1898.

00:46:19.696 --> 00:46:20.795
From Belgium.

00:46:20.862 --> 00:46:23.359
But the Euros
that came here back in the day.

00:46:23.426 --> 00:46:25.743
-Had no idea what they were getting into.
-No.

00:46:25.810 --> 00:46:27.763
They didn't speak English.

00:46:27.830 --> 00:46:29.884
She's a long cool woman in a black dress.

00:46:30.696 --> 00:46:32.726
[Peter] Murdered in 1905.

00:46:33.319 --> 00:46:37.283
"Was reputed to be the wealthiest
woman in the Arizona Territory."

00:46:37.350 --> 00:46:38.233
-I believe it.

00:46:43.200 --> 00:46:45.952
Let's check this out.
The Haunted Liberty Theater.

00:46:46.900 --> 00:46:48.135
Little movie day Bob.

00:46:49.063 --> 00:46:50.783
Look at this. Isn't it cool?

00:46:50.850 --> 00:46:52.016
Oh my god.

00:46:52.083 --> 00:46:55.147
I don't know if it's
gonna show up with the camera.

00:46:55.214 --> 00:46:56.228
Very steep.

00:46:56.295 --> 00:46:58.151
-Bob you alright?
-I'm fine.

00:46:58.218 --> 00:47:00.630
Look at these chairs. This is deluxe man.

00:47:01.921 --> 00:47:06.606
I think Black Betty over at the Bordello
is probably an investor in this place.

00:47:06.673 --> 00:47:08.293
[Peter] What a trippy place.

00:47:10.390 --> 00:47:13.668
Oh this is why they call it
the Haunted Movie Theater.

00:47:13.735 --> 00:47:14.853
[scary music plays]

00:47:30.046 --> 00:47:32.420
[Peter] Creepy zone slash museum, Jerome.

00:47:32.930 --> 00:47:35.812
[Bob] Crazy.
Would never have known this was here.

00:47:42.610 --> 00:47:45.669
-[Bob] That smells good.
-[Peter] Little bar in here.

00:47:50.530 --> 00:47:54.158
[Peter] Old school bar
next to new gift shop. Look at this.

00:47:54.610 --> 00:47:55.964
Bartlett Hotel.

00:47:56.635 --> 00:47:57.696
-It must have burned.

00:47:57.763 --> 00:48:02.363
-"First two story building in Jerome.
Had rooms for dances dining and sleeping."

00:48:02.430 --> 00:48:05.064
1898, the structure
was destroyed by a fire.

00:48:05.468 --> 00:48:08.731
I mean isn't that the Arizona story?
Destroyed by a fire.

00:48:09.300 --> 00:48:13.122
-How many times have we heard that?
-Oh it happens all the time. Whole towns.

00:48:13.189 --> 00:48:16.413
The mining company sold
portions of it for salvage in the 1950s.

00:48:16.480 --> 00:48:18.966
Removing the entire top floor.

00:48:19.520 --> 00:48:22.663
[Bob] Just imagine you came
to this town on business in 1925,

00:48:22.730 --> 00:48:23.613
1926.

00:48:25.170 --> 00:48:27.684
Oh here you go Bob. Here's a fire truck.

00:48:27.751 --> 00:48:28.634
That's a Dodge.

00:48:30.489 --> 00:48:31.372
Dodge Brothers.

00:48:31.808 --> 00:48:34.373
That's a little fire truck.
That's nice man.

00:48:35.470 --> 00:48:38.970
Maybe the smallest police station.
Have you seen one this small before?

00:48:39.037 --> 00:48:39.920
-No I have not.

00:48:41.350 --> 00:48:42.814
-And I have been here before.

00:48:42.881 --> 00:48:45.350
This restaurant is awesome. Great food.

00:48:45.417 --> 00:48:47.273
-The Clinkscale?
-The Clinkscale.

00:48:47.810 --> 00:48:49.575
I'll show a little view of it.

00:48:57.856 --> 00:49:01.089
-The town's a bit all over the place huh?
-So this town was dead.

00:49:01.162 --> 00:49:04.104
-And the artists brought it back.
Pretty cool.

00:49:04.483 --> 00:49:07.463
'60s, I think there were
like 50 people living up here.

00:49:07.530 --> 00:49:08.851
That must have been great.

00:49:08.918 --> 00:49:11.194
And then it just built momentum.

00:49:12.400 --> 00:49:14.753
And now you have a tourist place mostly.

00:49:15.520 --> 00:49:19.326
It's just fascinating to me,
how do you bring a Quincy, Illinois back?

00:49:19.393 --> 00:49:21.223
Bring a Gloucester, Ohio back?

00:49:21.290 --> 00:49:24.426
Does it have to die completely
for the artists to get in

00:49:24.907 --> 00:49:26.561
and start to try to do something?

00:49:26.628 --> 00:49:28.813
The artists come in when it's cheap.

00:49:28.880 --> 00:49:31.306
They can create their art
and it's inspirational.

00:49:31.373 --> 00:49:33.149
Like this is inspirational for art.

00:49:33.216 --> 00:49:34.099
-Absolutely.

00:49:34.950 --> 00:49:36.701
Yeah I wouldn't mind living here.

00:49:36.768 --> 00:49:38.546
If you come here in the 1960s.

00:49:38.613 --> 00:49:40.523
-A lot of confession happened here.

00:49:40.590 --> 00:49:42.296
[Bob] But were they contrite?

00:49:43.070 --> 00:49:44.188
Here, read this.

00:49:45.080 --> 00:49:46.536
What's a spirit box, Bob?

00:49:46.603 --> 00:49:48.021
Oh, listen to this.

00:49:48.088 --> 00:49:50.537
Often hand held radio scanning device

00:49:50.967 --> 00:49:52.930
used by paranormal investigators

00:49:53.595 --> 00:49:55.358
to communicate with spirits.

00:49:55.425 --> 00:49:58.786
Typically via
electronic voice phenomenon, EVP.

00:49:59.777 --> 00:50:02.935
It sweeps all through the AM-FM
frequencies creating white noise

00:50:03.002 --> 00:50:06.673
that believers think entities manipulate
to form audible words or phrases

00:50:06.740 --> 00:50:07.858
often in real time.

00:50:08.540 --> 00:50:11.103
So the idea is that
there's a lot of spirits here.

00:50:11.170 --> 00:50:14.099
And so apparently these guys come in here

00:50:14.166 --> 00:50:16.083
and try to get some spirits to talk.

00:50:23.920 --> 00:50:25.770
-[Peter] This looks like a hotel huh?

00:50:25.837 --> 00:50:28.393
[Bob] It does.
These are really high-end places too.

00:50:28.460 --> 00:50:30.284
[Peter] The gateway to nowhere.

00:50:30.760 --> 00:50:35.088
But this time of day right around now
that sun starts going down a little bit.

00:50:35.155 --> 00:50:38.233
-Little breeze, cools off in the shade.
-Yeah it feels good.

00:50:38.790 --> 00:50:40.319
The Asylum Restaurant, Bob.

00:50:41.857 --> 00:50:44.713
[Bob] So this was an asylum.
This was for crazy miners.

00:50:44.780 --> 00:50:46.473
-We gotta get the history on this place.

00:50:46.540 --> 00:50:49.295
Or you said it was an infirmary.

00:50:49.362 --> 00:50:50.297
-I thought it was.

00:50:50.364 --> 00:50:53.213
-Probably a ton of injuries.
-We're gonna find out.

00:50:53.992 --> 00:50:55.639
[Peter] Oh that's beautiful.

00:50:56.522 --> 00:50:57.993
So you have these tables.

00:50:58.996 --> 00:51:00.290
The windows open here.

00:51:01.436 --> 00:51:03.318
And just right out to that view.

00:51:07.850 --> 00:51:10.168
You know what
this feels like a little bit Bob?

00:51:10.235 --> 00:51:11.788
That hotel in The Shining.

00:51:11.855 --> 00:51:13.233
-Right?
-The Overlook.

00:51:13.300 --> 00:51:16.171
The Overlook. There you go.
You wanna check the lobby out?

00:51:16.238 --> 00:51:19.190
[Bob] All work and no play
makes Jack a dull boy.

00:51:20.170 --> 00:51:21.523
It's got Shining vibes.

00:51:22.212 --> 00:51:24.683
That's probably why they say it's haunted.

00:51:25.032 --> 00:51:26.318
Why thank you.

00:51:26.385 --> 00:51:27.268
Hi there.

00:51:27.739 --> 00:51:29.397
-How you doing?
-[woman] Good, and you?

00:51:29.464 --> 00:51:30.483
Doing great.

00:51:30.550 --> 00:51:33.261
-[Bob] What's the story in this place?
-[Peter] Asylum?

00:51:33.328 --> 00:51:35.156
No. The asylum is the restaurant.

00:51:35.223 --> 00:51:37.443
And that's just the name that they go by.

00:51:37.510 --> 00:51:40.752
They rent it from us so we're not gonna
ask them to change their name.

00:51:40.819 --> 00:51:43.305
This was a hospital. It was built in 1926.

00:51:43.987 --> 00:51:47.367
And it took them about nine months
to have it all built.

00:51:47.827 --> 00:51:50.882
By what 1927? It was up and open.

00:51:51.496 --> 00:51:55.704
And it's built on bedrock and it's cement
on top because the rest of Jerome

00:51:55.771 --> 00:51:59.179
moves about a half inch and they
didn't want this one to go anywhere.

00:51:59.246 --> 00:52:02.507
The staircases coming up here
in town were slanted.

00:52:02.574 --> 00:52:05.062
Yes. There were landslides in 1940.

00:52:05.862 --> 00:52:08.023
The Jerome Jail slid down the hill.

00:52:08.090 --> 00:52:10.395
They say it's haunted right?
Is that the story?

00:52:10.462 --> 00:52:13.274
Well yeah.
I mean it's an old hospital built in 1926.

00:52:13.341 --> 00:52:14.694
Of course it's haunted.

00:52:15.327 --> 00:52:17.734
We have Claude was found

00:52:17.801 --> 00:52:20.680
at the bottom of the elevator I believe.

00:52:21.232 --> 00:52:24.571
He was found
with his palms facing up which is weird

00:52:24.638 --> 00:52:26.936
but he was laying down on his back

00:52:27.003 --> 00:52:29.716
And then one of the nurses
crawled down the elevator

00:52:29.783 --> 00:52:31.750
and it unfortunately took off his head.

00:52:31.817 --> 00:52:35.874
But they did figure out that the
elevator isn't the reason that killed him

00:52:35.941 --> 00:52:38.067
but they never figured out more than that.

00:52:38.134 --> 00:52:40.645
So we do know that Otis isn't responsible.

00:52:40.712 --> 00:52:42.193
Oh the manufacturer, Otis.

00:52:42.260 --> 00:52:44.933
[Bob] There had to be
a lot of injuries in the mines.

00:52:45.000 --> 00:52:48.042
Yeah I mean they had lit
kerosene lamps on their faces

00:52:48.109 --> 00:52:50.037
going a thousand feet into the ground.

00:52:50.104 --> 00:52:51.467
-Yeah.
-[laughter]

00:52:51.541 --> 00:52:53.740
[Bob] My family's miners so I know.

00:52:53.807 --> 00:52:55.959
-They were getting that copper.
-Absolutely.

00:52:56.026 --> 00:52:59.490
And then the main mine,
the United Copper Verde Mine Company,

00:52:59.557 --> 00:53:03.607
they had a steam shovel explosion
blow up their tunnel entrance

00:53:03.674 --> 00:53:05.634
so they went to an open pit mine.

00:53:05.701 --> 00:53:06.847
-Oh okay.

00:53:07.355 --> 00:53:09.533
The other one the Audrey Headframe,

00:53:09.600 --> 00:53:12.476
that's the one over by
the State Park down there.

00:53:12.543 --> 00:53:14.504
You can
kind of see the framework of it.

00:53:14.571 --> 00:53:17.662
That one was the one that stayed over time.

00:53:18.555 --> 00:53:21.377
So there's hundreds of mines
and tunnels under this town.

00:53:21.444 --> 00:53:23.503
Oh really? It's Swiss cheese under here?

00:53:23.570 --> 00:53:26.175
Just not under us but under the town, yes.

00:53:26.584 --> 00:53:30.520
If you go exploring up some of the
mountains you can find some of the mines.

00:53:30.587 --> 00:53:31.927
I wouldn't recommend.

00:53:31.994 --> 00:53:34.481
-No, we're good.
-Most are filled with water.

00:53:34.548 --> 00:53:37.121
You take a rock and you listen to it fall.

00:53:37.188 --> 00:53:38.894
You might drown. Don't do it.

00:53:38.961 --> 00:53:40.314
[Bob] I'm not doing it.

00:53:41.110 --> 00:53:43.608
So what's it like living up here?

00:53:43.675 --> 00:53:45.263
-It sounds awesome.
-Awesome.

00:53:46.420 --> 00:53:48.596
[Peter] Thanks ladies. Appreciate it.

00:53:49.042 --> 00:53:51.564
People can stay here now. Rooms for rent.

00:53:52.399 --> 00:53:53.282
[Bob] 50 cent.

00:53:54.727 --> 00:53:58.080
Well how much are they?
Does it show in this brochure Bob?

00:54:00.387 --> 00:54:01.613
[Peter] There you go.

00:54:01.680 --> 00:54:04.283
$220, $250, $300, $385.

00:54:08.680 --> 00:54:11.000
That's probably the car
that the hotel sent out

00:54:11.067 --> 00:54:13.403
to pick up people at the train station.

00:54:13.470 --> 00:54:15.294
That's a Rolls Royce limousine.

00:54:15.684 --> 00:54:18.220
Here's another one. This is a Pierce Arrow.

00:54:18.287 --> 00:54:20.360
-You know this?
-This is a great vehicle.

00:54:20.427 --> 00:54:22.393
Now what I was saying about Jay Leno,

00:54:22.460 --> 00:54:24.393
he was saying these old cars,

00:54:24.460 --> 00:54:27.358
he has a Pierce Arrow
and the only thing he had to do

00:54:27.425 --> 00:54:30.668
was change the battery
because the old batteries were leaking.

00:54:30.735 --> 00:54:34.048
But they have truck frames.
You know, they're really solid.

00:54:34.522 --> 00:54:36.148
What I'm trying to say is that

00:54:36.215 --> 00:54:38.765
everyone thinks this stuff
is really old and rickety

00:54:38.832 --> 00:54:41.356
but it was the apex
of the technology of the age

00:54:41.423 --> 00:54:43.809
and it worked, it all worked.

00:54:44.360 --> 00:54:48.308
So you had this age, this sort of flowering
of the Industrial Revolution,

00:54:48.375 --> 00:54:52.163
the first part
of the flowering of the revolution,

00:54:52.230 --> 00:54:53.554
the Industrial Revolution.

00:54:53.621 --> 00:54:56.823
Cars, heat, mining,
all these things happening

00:54:57.270 --> 00:55:00.424
and to live in that time
it must have been incredible

00:55:00.491 --> 00:55:03.726
because you would have thought,
"Oh wow, this is great."

00:55:04.223 --> 00:55:08.116
That Pierce Arrow you wouldn't
even know you were riding in a car.

00:55:08.183 --> 00:55:11.503
I think of tourists
from around the world, say Asia or Europe,

00:55:11.570 --> 00:55:15.087
yes, LA, New York,
fantastic places, great to visit.

00:55:15.154 --> 00:55:17.801
But if they did this trip
we've done today Bob

00:55:18.288 --> 00:55:20.380
just blow their minds don't you think?

00:55:20.447 --> 00:55:22.847
'Cause it's…
nothing like this exists anywhere.

00:55:22.914 --> 00:55:26.051
Well it's a different world
that people don't realize.

00:55:26.118 --> 00:55:28.395
There are places like this
all over the place.

00:55:28.462 --> 00:55:31.566
Up in Montana
there's mining towns, all kinds of stuff.

00:55:31.633 --> 00:55:32.680
It's endless.

00:55:32.747 --> 00:55:36.363
And if you are interested in history
this is how you learn history.

00:55:36.430 --> 00:55:39.426
You know I learned
because I would visit some place and go,

00:55:39.493 --> 00:55:41.003
"Oh that's how that worked."

00:55:41.410 --> 00:55:43.561
What you do, the lifestyle you live,

00:55:44.123 --> 00:55:46.876
in this country
you can constantly discover.

00:55:46.943 --> 00:55:48.547
-That's the beauty of it.
-Yes.

00:55:48.614 --> 00:55:50.471
You can constantly explore and learn.

00:55:50.538 --> 00:55:52.407
Well that's what I decided last year.

00:55:52.474 --> 00:55:55.331
I do not want to sit in the desert
with a bunch of people

00:55:55.398 --> 00:55:57.979
b*tching and moaning
for the entire winter.

00:55:58.046 --> 00:56:00.838
I want to go to places
and different places.

00:56:00.905 --> 00:56:04.499
And I need to obviously work on
getting the funding to do that.

00:56:04.566 --> 00:56:07.438
I want to stay traveling,
going places, and seeing things.

00:56:07.505 --> 00:56:09.233
I don't want to just sit.

00:56:09.300 --> 00:56:12.511
And for those that don't know
Bob has an awesome YouTube channel.

00:56:12.578 --> 00:56:15.936
Talks story,
talks history in these beautiful places.

00:56:16.003 --> 00:56:19.261
Shows the life of Unit 11
which we haven't shown much of today.

00:56:19.328 --> 00:56:22.963
-Today's been more about the locations.
-Unit 11 is a supporting actor.

00:56:23.030 --> 00:56:25.501
Yeah exactly.
He's a character actor today.

00:56:26.317 --> 00:56:28.321
Very important though for the story.

00:56:28.388 --> 00:56:29.990
And he has a podcast.

00:56:30.371 --> 00:56:32.693
You're gonna see when
we go down this mountain.

00:56:32.760 --> 00:56:34.838
We're gonna be going very slow

00:56:34.905 --> 00:56:36.862
because that truck is heavy enough

00:56:36.929 --> 00:56:39.517
that it will gain speed
and it won't be good.

00:56:39.584 --> 00:56:42.423
Getting over, I don't know if it's
7,000 feet, 8,000 feet.

00:56:42.490 --> 00:56:44.781
-Yeah it's 7,000 feet.
-Up to Mingus Mountain.

00:56:45.278 --> 00:56:47.914
And then coming into
a whole different valley.

00:56:47.981 --> 00:56:50.773
-Whole different reality.
-Yes, whole different reality.

00:56:50.840 --> 00:56:52.100
[Western music]

00:56:52.167 --> 00:56:55.579
[Bob] Watch that wall.
Don't let it get close to that wall.

00:56:56.604 --> 00:57:00.454
[Peter] Bob do you ever feel like 
you overdid it with the size of this thing?

00:57:00.521 --> 00:57:02.623
-Well I do now. No, I love this thing.

00:57:02.690 --> 00:57:05.453
-What's the gas mileage?
-10 miles to the gallon.

00:57:05.520 --> 00:57:08.463
As my dad said
it'll pass anything but a gas station.

00:57:08.530 --> 00:57:09.589
[music continues]

00:57:13.000 --> 00:57:14.353
Oh my God, look at that.

00:57:22.869 --> 00:57:24.503
[Bob] I can feel the breeze up here.

00:57:24.570 --> 00:57:27.443
[Peter] -It's so much cooler huh?
It feels great.

00:57:27.510 --> 00:57:31.829
We have these tall pines here.
We're up at altitude, roughly 7,000 feet.

00:57:32.290 --> 00:57:35.940
Less temperature, more moisture
in the winter and the summers.

00:57:36.484 --> 00:57:40.593
[Bob] Again, it's another one of those
unique things about Arizona.

00:57:40.660 --> 00:57:41.860
[music continues]

00:57:44.090 --> 00:57:47.290
Bob, little update here on the descent.
What do you think so far?

00:57:47.357 --> 00:57:49.636
-Well so far so good.
-You weren't that guy.

00:57:49.703 --> 00:57:51.163
He left his bumper there.

00:57:51.230 --> 00:57:53.503
-Wasn't too bad Bob?
-Wasn't too bad.

00:57:53.570 --> 00:57:55.085
I'm not smelling the brakes.

00:57:55.570 --> 00:57:58.470
We had to take this mountain.
This was a good way to do it.

00:57:58.980 --> 00:58:02.413
[Peter] This is Prescott Valley I believe.
That's how the locals say it.

00:58:02.500 --> 00:58:04.157
"Preskit" not Prescott.

00:58:04.224 --> 00:58:06.853
I don't call it Prescott either.
I call it "Preskit".

00:58:06.920 --> 00:58:10.470
[Peter] So you can see we got
a bunch of new home developments here Bob.

00:58:10.537 --> 00:58:11.420
-We sure do.

00:58:11.487 --> 00:58:14.829
-A place where I think
a lot of people from from the Midwest

00:58:14.896 --> 00:58:17.226
have moved out here
from all over the country.

00:58:17.293 --> 00:58:21.068
Seeking sunny weather,
warmer weather, cheaper living costs.

00:58:21.136 --> 00:58:24.158
I asked you off camera,
I'll ask you again,

00:58:24.598 --> 00:58:28.889
Top three states if you gotta settle down,
can't go anywhere, what are they?

00:58:28.956 --> 00:58:30.039
Arizona,

00:58:30.106 --> 00:58:32.145
California by the Green River,

00:58:32.743 --> 00:58:35.440
San Bernardino, going west towards LA.

00:58:36.110 --> 00:58:37.478
I do like Tennessee.

00:58:37.545 --> 00:58:40.133
There's some pretty cool places
in Tennessee.

00:58:41.470 --> 00:58:44.817
[Peter] Here we are in Prescott,
food truck scene, The Yard.

00:58:45.564 --> 00:58:47.578
And here we got a cool downtown.

00:58:48.212 --> 00:58:50.013
Bob what do you know about Prescott?

00:58:50.080 --> 00:58:54.067
-Well this was the original capital
of the state, the territorial capital.

00:58:54.134 --> 00:58:55.017
-Ranching?

00:58:55.084 --> 00:58:57.607
Also it was a mining service.

00:58:57.674 --> 00:59:00.091
So services, banks, things that mines need.

00:59:00.158 --> 00:59:02.305
So this town also served the mines.

00:59:02.740 --> 00:59:05.411
This is a big town
compared to where we've been today.

00:59:05.484 --> 00:59:07.257
-This video is getting pretty long.

00:59:07.324 --> 00:59:09.832
I say we just go to
the downtown here check it out.

00:59:09.899 --> 00:59:14.582
This town deserves a completely separate
video on its own some other time.

00:59:16.937 --> 00:59:18.787
-How you doing?
-I watch you videos.

00:59:18.854 --> 00:59:20.585
-Thank you.
-What is this rig?!

00:59:20.652 --> 00:59:22.534
-We're making a video right now.
-Right on.

00:59:22.601 --> 00:59:23.866
My name's Randy.

00:59:23.933 --> 00:59:25.096
-You're from here?
-Yes.

00:59:25.163 --> 00:59:26.893
-How is it?
-It's good, I love it.

00:59:26.960 --> 00:59:28.908
Mountain biking, small town feel.

00:59:28.975 --> 00:59:30.853
Alright. I love Arizona.

00:59:30.920 --> 00:59:32.673
I dig what you do. Thank you.

00:59:33.320 --> 00:59:36.873
-You gotta love the Western wear huh?
-The Western wear.

00:59:36.940 --> 00:59:39.062
[Peter] What's your shirt say sir?

00:59:39.129 --> 00:59:41.279
"It's not my fault
I was left unsupervised."

00:59:42.080 --> 00:59:43.897
-Are you guys from Prescott?
-Yes.

00:59:43.964 --> 00:59:45.393
-How is it?
-Great.

00:59:45.460 --> 00:59:47.460
Great huh? Beautiful out here.

00:59:47.527 --> 00:59:50.053
It is beautiful.
It's a nice small community

00:59:50.120 --> 00:59:52.635
and there's always
lots of extra activities going on.

00:59:52.702 --> 00:59:55.038
-Looks nice.
-Whiskey Row if that's your thing.

00:59:55.105 --> 00:59:57.163
-That's what this is called?
-Yep.

00:59:57.230 --> 00:59:58.780
[man] Howdy. How we doing?

00:59:58.847 --> 01:00:00.529
-[man] Good How we doing? 
-Hi guys.

01:00:00.596 --> 01:00:02.963
[Peter] It's got like a
solid Western feel Bob.

01:00:03.030 --> 01:00:03.913
Yes.

01:00:03.980 --> 01:00:05.459
Like cowboy ranching feel.

01:00:05.526 --> 01:00:07.016
Here's the interesting thing.

01:00:07.083 --> 01:00:10.846
The more time I spend in the West
the less I notice the Western stuff.

01:00:10.913 --> 01:00:12.035
It's very interesting.

01:00:12.102 --> 01:00:15.668
When I first came out here
I could just feel being in the West.

01:00:15.735 --> 01:00:16.735
This is the West.

01:00:17.131 --> 01:00:18.752
Now I'm kind of used to it.

01:00:18.819 --> 01:00:21.120
So I have to remind myself.

01:00:21.886 --> 01:00:25.360
[man] Let's mug the guy with the pizza.
He's got pizza. Let's mug him.

01:00:25.427 --> 01:00:27.929
-He's walking away from us understandably.

01:00:27.996 --> 01:00:29.343
Oldest rodeo I read.

01:00:29.410 --> 01:00:31.962
Yes. 1888 I believe.

01:00:32.029 --> 01:00:34.508
Right up there. World's oldest rodeo, 1888.

01:00:34.575 --> 01:00:35.869
Right in the building.

01:00:36.560 --> 01:00:38.285
-[man] Enjoy.
-[Peter] Take care.

01:00:40.100 --> 01:00:41.215
[Bob] This has just been great.

01:00:41.282 --> 01:00:44.247
How many people when they think of Arizona,

01:00:44.314 --> 01:00:49.013
you think of Arizona highways,
Phoenix, golf, you think of all this stuff.

01:00:49.080 --> 01:00:52.256
My own personal feeling is
that the history of the West

01:00:52.745 --> 01:00:54.922
is really the history of the United States.

01:00:54.989 --> 01:00:58.963
Almost more than
the Revolutionary or the Civil War periods.

01:00:59.606 --> 01:01:03.546
Because the West is really all about
opportunity and people moving west

01:01:03.613 --> 01:01:06.308
to build and grow and do things.

01:01:07.184 --> 01:01:09.171
That is still a factor.

01:01:09.238 --> 01:01:10.709
People are moving to Arizona.

01:01:10.776 --> 01:01:14.506
People are moving out West
to different places, Montana, Wyoming

01:01:14.573 --> 01:01:16.038
to start something new.

01:01:16.105 --> 01:01:17.473
To get away from

01:01:17.986 --> 01:01:20.113
the quote unquote "rat race".

01:01:20.180 --> 01:01:23.889
Alright guys. Just want to let you know
Bob has his own podcast

01:01:23.956 --> 01:01:25.389
more about Unit 11.

01:01:25.830 --> 01:01:29.203
The nuts and bolts of it.
